{"title_page": "Base erosion and profit shifting", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2018}}\n{{short description|Multinational tax avoidance tools}}\n\n{{Taxation}}\n\n[[File:Treasury Department rear view.JPG|thumb|The [[United States Department of the Treasury]] decided against signing the 2016 OECD anti\u2013BEPS MLI initiative from the {{slink|#OECD BEPS Project}}, stating that the U.S.: \"has a low degree of exposure to base erosion and profit shifting\".<ref name=\"baker\"/>\n International tax academics showed in 2018 that U.S. multinationals are the largest users of BEPS tools in the world;<ref name=\"zucwright\"/> while U.S tax academics demonstrated, even as early as 1994, that the U.S. exchequer is a net beneficiary from the use of tax havens and BEPS by U.S. multinationals.<ref name=\"h1\"/><ref name=\"dryng\"/>]]\n\n'''Base erosion and profit shifting''' ('''BEPS''') refers to corporate [[tax planning]] strategies used by [[multinational companies|multinationals]] to \"shift\" profits from higher-tax jurisdictions to lower-tax jurisdictions, thus \"eroding\" the \"tax-base\" of the higher-tax jurisdictions.<ref name=\"be\"/><ref name=\"oecd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oecd.org/tax/beps/|title=OECD Base Erosion and Profit Shifting}}</ref>\n\nThe [[OECD|Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] (OECD) define BEPS strategies as also \"exploiting gaps and mismatches in tax rules\";<ref name=\"oecd\"/> however, academics proved corporate [[tax havens]] (such as Ireland, the Caribbean, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Singapore, Switzerland, and Hong Kong),{{efn|These are also the largest [[offshore financial centres]] (\"OFCs\"); a term considered by academics to be synonymous with the term [[tax haven]]}} who are the largest [[Corporate haven#Global BEPS hubs|global BEPS hubs]], use OECD\u2013whitelisted tax structures and OECD\u2013compliant BEPS tools.<ref name=\"zux\"/><ref name=\"be\"/>\n\n[[Corporate tax haven]]s offer BEPS tools to \"shift\" profits to the haven, and additional BEPS tools to avoid paying taxes within the haven (e.g. Ireland's \"[[Ireland as a tax haven#Green Jersey|CAIA tool]]\").{{efn|The ''[[Capital Allowances for Intangible Assets]]'' (CAIA) BEPS tool, also known as the ''Green Jersey'', was the BEPS tool Apple used in Q1 2015 to restructure its non-U.S. IP. It created the famous \"[[leprechaun economics]]\" event in Ireland in August 2016, when restated Irish GDP rose 34.4% in a single quarter}} BEPS tools are associated mostly with U.S. [[technology]] and [[life science]] multinationals.{{efn|name=\"ip\"|The critical component of the most important BEPS tools is [[intellectual property]] (\"IP\"), which the BEPS tool converts into a charge that is deductible against pre\u2013tax income. Technology and Life Sciences industries have the largest pools of IP.}}<ref name=\"zucwright\"/> Tax academics showed use of the BEPS tools by U.S. multinationals, via [[tax havens]], maximised long\u2013term U.S. exchequer receipts and shareholder return, at the expense of others.<ref name=\"h1\"/><ref name=\"dryng\"/><ref name=\"zucwright\"/>\n\n==Scale==\nIn January 2017, the OECD estimated that BEPS tools are responsible for tax losses of circa $100\u2013240 billion per annum.<ref name=\"BEPS Background\">{{cite web|title=BEPS Project Background Brief| url=http://www.oecd.org/tax/beps/background-brief-inclusive-framework-for-beps-implementation.pdf|publisher=[[OECD]]|quote=With a conservatively estimated annual revenue loss of USD 100 to 240 billion, the stakes are high for governments around the world. The impact of BEPS on developing countries, as a percentage of tax revenues, is estimated to be even higher than in developed countries.|date=January 2017|page=9}}</ref> In June 2018, an investigation by tax academic [[Gabriel Zucman]] (et alia),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gabriel-zucman.eu/missingprofits/|title=The Missing Profits of Nations|quote=Appendix Table 2: Tax Havens|page=31|author1=Gabriel Zucman|author2=Thomas Torslov|author3=Ludvig Wier|publisher=[[National Bureau of Economic Research]], Working Papers|date=June 2018|author1-link=Gabriel Zucman}}</ref> estimated that the figure is closer to $200 billion per annum.<ref name=\"zuc10\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/corporations-push-profits-into-tax-havens-as-countries-struggle-in-pursuit-study-says-1528634659|title=Zucman:Corporations Push Profits Into Corporate Tax Havens as Countries Struggle in Pursuit, Gabrial Zucman Study Says|quote=Such profit shifting leads to a total annual revenue loss of $200 billion globally|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=10 June 2018}}</ref> The [[Tax Justice Network]] estimated that profits of $660 billion were \"shifted\" in 2015 (due to Apple's Q 2015 [[leprechaun economics]] restructuring, the largest individual BEPS transaction in history<ref name=\"cofr\"/>).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.taxjustice.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Tax-dodging-the-scale-of-the-problem-TJN-Briefing.pdf|title=Tax avoidance and evasion: The scale of the problem|publisher=[[Tax Justice Network]]|date=17 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The scale of Base Erosion and Profit Shifting (BEPS): Tax Justice Network|url=http://www.taxjustice.net/scalebeps/|website=[[Tax Justice Network]]}}</ref> The effect of BEPS tools is most felt in developing economies, who are denied the tax revenues needed to build infrastructure.<ref name=\"un1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.taxjustice.net/2017/09/11/new-un-tax-handbook-sets-lower-income-countries-oecd-beps/|title=New UN tax handbook: Lower\u2013income countries vs OECD BEPS failure|publisher=Tax Justice Network| date=11 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/nov/08/tax-havens-dodging-theft-multinationals-avoiding-tax|title=The desperate inequality behind global tax dodging|work=The Guardian| date=8 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nMost BEPS activity is associated with industries with [[intellectual property]] (\"IP\"), namely Technology (e.g. Apple, Google, Microsoft, Oracle), and Life Sciences (e.g. Allergan, Medtronic, Pfizer and Merck & Co) (see [[double Irish#US multinationals using Irish tax schemes|here]]).{{efn|name=\"ip\"}}<ref name=\"alex\">{{cite web|url=https://www.taxjustice.net/2018/07/24/progress-global-profit-shifting/|title=Progress on global profit shifting: no more hiding for jurisdictions that sell profit shifting at the expense of others|date=24 July 2018|author=Alex Cobham|quote=..for US multinationals, the real explosion in profit shifting began in the 1990s. At this point, a \u2018mere\u2019 5\u201310% of global profits were declared away from the jurisdictions of the underlying real economic activity. By the early 2010s, that had soared to 25\u201330% of global profits, with an estimated revenue loss of around $130 billion a year..|publisher=[[Tax Justice Network]]}}</ref> IP is described as the ''raw materials of tax avoidance'', and [[Corporate haven#IP-based BEPS tools|IP\u2013based BEPS tools]] are responsible for the largest global BEPS income flows.<ref name=\"ucla\">{{cite web | url=https://www.uclalawreview.org/pdf/62-1-1.pdf | title=Intellectual Property Law Solutions to Tax Avoidance | author=Andrew Blair-Stanek|quote=Intellectual property (IP) has become the leading tax-avoidance vehicle.| publisher=UCLA Law Review |year=2015}}</ref><ref name=\"fordam\">{{cite web | url=http://www.fordhamiplj.org/2016/08/30/ip-tax-avoidance-ireland/ | title=Intellectual Property and Tax Avoidance in Ireland | publisher=[[Fordham Intellectual Property, Media & Entertainment Law Journal]] | date=30 August 2016}}</ref> Corporate tax havens have some of the most [[Corporate haven#The \"Knowledge Economy\"|advanced IP tax leglislation]] in their statute books.<ref name=\"ip\"/>\n\nMost BEPS activity is also most associated with U.S. multinationals,<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/corporations-push-profits-into-tax-havens-as-countries-struggle-in-pursuit-study-says-1528634659|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|author= Richard Rubin|quote=U.S. companies are the most aggressive users of profit-shifting techniques, which often relocate paper profits without bringing jobs and wages, according to the study by economists Thomas Torslov and Ludvig Wier of the University of Copenhagen and Gabriel Zucman of the University of California, Berkeley|date=10 June 2018|title=Corporations Push Profits Into Tax Havens as Countries Struggle in Pursuit, Study Says}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nordic.businessinsider.com/new-research-finds-40-of-multinationals-profits-shifted-to-tax-havens--eu-biggest-loser-while-us-firms-most-shifty--/|website=[[Business Insider]]|title=New research finds 40% of multinationals' profits shifted to tax havens \u2013 EU biggest loser while US firms most shifty|date=20 July 2018|access-date=31 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831002541/https://nordic.businessinsider.com/new-research-finds-40-of-multinationals-profits-shifted-to-tax-havens--eu-biggest-loser-while-us-firms-most-shifty--/|archive-date=31 August 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"be\"/><ref name=\"alex\"/> and is attributed to the historical U.S. \"worldwide\" corporate taxation system.<ref name=\"be\"/><ref name=\"hines2016\">{{cite journal| url = https://repository.law.umich.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2831&context=articles|title=Multinational Firms and Tax Havens|author1=James R. Hines Jr.|author2=Anna Gumpert|author3=Monika Schnitzer|year=2016|journal=[[The Review of Economics and Statistics]]|page=714|quote=Germany taxes only 5% of the active foreign business profits of its resident corporations. [..] Furthermore, German firms do not have incentives to structure their foreign operations in ways that avoid repatriating income. Therefore, the tax incentives for German firms to establish tax haven affiliates are likely to differ from those of U.S. firms and bear strong similarities to those of other G-7 and OECD firms.|volume=98|issue=4|author1-link=James R. Hines Jr}}</ref> Pre the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]] (TCJA), the U.S. was one of only eight jurisdictions to operate a \"worldwide\" tax system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/wp/2013/wp13205.pdf|title=Territorial vs. Worldwide Corporate Taxation: Implications for Developing Countries|publisher=IMF|year=2013|page=4}}</ref> Most global jurisdictions operate a \"territorial\" corporate tax system with lower tax rates for foreign sourced income, thus avoiding the need to \"shift\" profits (i.e. IP can be charged directly from the home country at preferential rates and/or terms; post the 2017 TCJA, this happens in the U.S. via the FDII-regime).<ref name=\"uuu1\">{{cite web|url=https://files.taxfoundation.org/legacy/docs/TaxFoundation_FF442.pdf | title=Tax Reform in the UK Reversed the Tide of Corporate Tax Inversions | publisher=Tax Foundation| date=14 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"uk1\">{{cite web|url= https://taxfoundation.org/tax-reform-uk-reversed-tide-corporate-tax-inversions/|title=How Tax Reform solved UK inversions|publisher=Tax Foundation|date=14 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"uktax1\">{{cite web|url= https://taxfoundation.org/united-kingdom-s-experience-inversions/|title=The United Kingdom's Experience with Inversions|publisher=Tax Foundation|date=5 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|U.S. multinationals use tax havens{{efn|The paper lists tax havens as: ''Ireland, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Switzerland, Singapore, Bermuda and Caribbean havens'' (page 6.)}} more than multinationals from other countries which have kept their controlled foreign corporations regulations. No other non\u2013haven OECD country records as high a share of foreign profits booked in tax havens as the United States. [...] This suggests that half of all the global profits shifted to tax havens, are shifted by U.S. multinationals. By contrast, about 25% accrues to E.U. countries, 10% to the rest of the OECD, and 15% to developing countries (T\u00f8rsl\u00f8v et al., 2018).|source=[[Gabriel Zucman]], Thomas Wright, \"THE EXORBITANT TAX PRIVILEGE\", [[National Bureau of Economic Research|NBER]] Working Papers (September 2018).<ref name=\"zucwright\">{{cite journal|url=http://gabriel-zucman.eu/files/WrightZucman2018.pdf|title=THE EXORBITANT TAX PRIVILEGE|publisher=[[National Bureau of Economic Research]]|author1=Gabriel Zucman|page=11|author2=Thomas Wright|date=September 2018|author1-link=Gabriel Zucman}}</ref>}}\n\nResearch in June 2018 identified Ireland as the world's largest BEPS hub.<ref name=\"gabrielzucman\"/> Ireland is larger than the ''aggregate'' Caribbean tax haven BEPS system.<ref name=\"zux\">{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/economy/ireland-is-the-world-s-biggest-corporate-tax-haven-say-academics-1.3528401?mode=sample&auth-failed=1&pw-origin=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.irishtimes.com%2Fbusiness%2Feconomy%2Fireland-is-the-world-s-biggest-corporate-tax-haven-say-academics-1.3528401|title=Ireland is the world's biggest corporate 'tax haven', say academics|quote=New Gabriel Zucman study claims State shelters more multinational profits than the entire Caribbean|work=The Irish Times|date=13 June 2018}}</ref> The largest global BEPS hubs, from the [[Gabriel Zucman#Zucman-T\u00f8rsl\u00f8v-Wier 2018 list|Zucman\u2013T\u00f8rsl\u00f8v\u2013Wier]] table below, are synonymous with the [[Tax haven#Top 10 tax havens|top 10 global tax havens]]:\n{{anchor|Table 1}}\n[[File:Where do U.S. multinationals book their profits (2016 BEA).png|thumb|upright=1.6|U.S. multinationals book over half of their non\u2013U.S. profits in tax havens by using BEPS tools (2016 [[Bureau of Economic Analysis|BEA]]).<ref name=\"zucwright\"/><ref name=\"japantimes\"/>]]\n{| style=\"font-size:100%;\"\n|-\n| width=\"50%\" align=\"left\" |\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ style=\"text-align: left;\" | Zucman\u2013T\u00f8rsl\u00f8v\u2013Wier. ''Missing Profits of Nations''. Table 1: Shifted Profits (2015)<ref name=\"gabrielzucman\">{{cite web|url=http://gabriel-zucman.eu/|title=The Missing Profits of Nations|page=31|author1=Gabriel Zucman|author2=Thomas Torslov|author3=Ludvig Wier|quote=Table 2: Shifted Profits: Country\u2013by\u2013Country Estimates (2015)|publisher=[[National Bureau of Economic Research]], Working Papers|date=June 2018|author1-link=Gabriel Zucman}}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"background:#cfc;width:120px;text-align:left\" | Profits Shifted<br>(2015 $ bn)<ref name=\"gabrielzucman\"/>\n! style=\"width:190px;text-align:left\" | Jurisdiction\n! style=\"width:200px;text-align:left\" | Headline Corporate Tax Rate<br>(all firms) (%)\n! style=\"width:200px;text-align:left\" | Effective Corporate Tax Rate<br>(foreign firms) (%)<ref name=\"gabrielzucman\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | 106 || align=\"left\" | Ireland                  || align=\"right\" |  12.5 || align=\"right\" |  4 \n|-                                                                                                           \n| align=\"right\" |  97 || align=\"left\" | Caribbean\u2020 (ex. Bermuda) || align=\"right\" | <3    || align=\"right\" |  2  \n|-                                                                                                           \n| align=\"right\" |  70 || align=\"left\" | Singapore                || align=\"right\" |  17   || align=\"right\" |  8  \n|-                                                                                                           \n| align=\"right\" |  58 || align=\"left\" | Switzerland              || align=\"right\" |  21   || align=\"right\" | 16  \n|-                                                                                                           \n| align=\"right\" |  57 || align=\"left\" | Netherlands              || align=\"right\" |  25   || align=\"right\" | 10  \n|-                                                                                                           \n| align=\"right\" |  47 || align=\"left\" | Luxembourg               || align=\"right\" |  29   || align=\"right\" |  3  \n|-                                                                                                           \n| align=\"right\" |  39 || align=\"left\" | Hong Kong                || align=\"right\" |  18   || align=\"right\" | 18  \n|}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|}\n(\u2020) Mostly consists of The Cayman Islands and The British Virgin Islands\n\nResearch in September 2018, by the [[National Bureau of Economic Research]], using repatriation tax data from the TCJA, said that: \"In recent years, about half of the foreign profits of U.S. multinationals have been booked in tax haven affiliates, most prominently in Ireland (18%), Switzerland, and Bermuda plus Caribbean tax havens (8%\u20139% each).<ref name=\"zucwright\"/> One of the authors of this research was also quoted as saying, \"Ireland solidifies its position as the #1 tax haven.... U.S. firms book more profits in Ireland than in China, Japan, Germany, France & Mexico combined. Irish tax rate: 5.7%.\"<ref name=\"japantimes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2018/09/11/business/half-u-s-foreign-profits-booked-tax-havens-especially-ireland-paper/#.W5eRKkZKhPY|title=Half of U.S. foreign profits booked in tax havens, especially Ireland: NBER paper|publisher=[[The Japan Times]]|quote=\u201cIreland solidifies its position as the #1 tax haven,\u201d Zucman said on Twitter. \u201cU.S. firms book more profits in Ireland than in China, Japan, Germany, France & Mexico combined. Irish tax rate: 5.7%.\u201d|date=10 September 2018|newspaper=The Japan Times Online}}</ref>\n\n==Tools==\n{{main|Corporate haven#Global BEPS hubs}}\n\nResearch identifies three main BEPS techniques used for \"shifting\" profits to a [[corporate tax haven]] via OECD\u2013compliant BEPS tools:<ref name=\"zew\">{{cite web|url=http://ftp.zew.de/pub/zew-docs/dp/dp13078.pdf|title=Profit Shifting and \"Aggressive\" Tax Planning by Multinational Firms|publisher=[[Zentrum f\u00fcr Europ\u00e4ische Wirtschaftsforschung|Centre for European Economic Research]], (ZEW)|author1=Clemens Fuest|author2=Christoph Spengel|author3=Katharina Finke|author4=Jost Heckemeyer|author5=Hannah Nusser|date=15 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"tilburg\">{{cite web | url=http://arno.uvt.nl/show.cgi?fid=143915| title=Intellectual Property Tax Planning in the light of Base Erosion and Profit Shifting | publisher=University of Tilburg | date=June 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{ordered list|type=lower-roman\n|[[Corporate haven#IP-based BEPS tools|IP\u2013based BEPS tools]],{{efn|name=\"IP\"|Some academics consider IP\u2013based BEPS tools to be a subset of TP\u2013based BEPS tools (e.g. the corporate is transfer pricing the IP like any other product), however others consider IP to be a unique item (e.g. the IP is a ''virtual product'' whose value is decided internally by the corporation; it is more of an accounting invention rather than a tangible good), that it is a separate set.}} which enable the profits to be extracted via the cross\u2013border charge\u2013out of internal virtual IP assets (known as \"intergroup IP charging\"); and/or\n|[[Corporate haven#Debt-based BEPS tools|Debt\u2013based BEPS tools]], which enable the profits to be extracted via the cross\u2013border charge\u2013out artificially high interest (known as \"earnings stripping\"); and/or\n|[[TP\u2013based BEPS tools]],{{efn|name=\"IP\"}} shifts profits to the haven by asserting that a ''process'' performed in the haven (e.g., [[contract manufacturing]]), justifies a large increase in the [[Transfer pricing|transfer price]] (\"TP\") at which the finished product is charged\u2013out by the haven to higher\u2013tax jurisdictions.\n}}\n\nBEPS tools could not function if the corporate tax haven did not have a network of bilateral tax treaties that accept the haven\u2019s BEPS tools, which \"shift\" the profits to the haven. Modern corporate tax havens, which are the main global BEPS hubs, have extensive networks of bilateral tax treaties.<ref name=\"dhh\">{{cite journal| url=https://academic.oup.com/oxrep/article/24/4/661/547359#|title=What Problems and Opportunities are Created by Tax Havens?|author=Dhammika Dharmapala|journal=[[Oxford Review of Economic Policy]]|page=3|date=December 2008|volume=24|issue=4|author-link=Dhammika Dharmapala}}</ref> The U.K. is the leader with over 122, followed by the Netherlands with over 100.<ref name=\"ukx\">{{cite journal|title=The Tax Treaty Network of the United Kingdom|url =http://www.fieldtax.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/2013-9-ILT-247-The-Tax-Treaty-Network-of-the-United-Kingdom1.pdf|journal=International Taxation|volume=9|issue=13|quote=The United Kingdom has 122 bilateral, comprehensive, double taxation conventions in force. It remains the largest number of tax treaties of any one country in the world. The United Kingdom may no longer be the world leader in manufacturing cars, or in playing football... however we are still the leading country in the world in negotiating double taxation conventions.|author=Philip Baker OBE QC|date=September 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"ukx1\">{{Cite web|title = UK tops global table of damaging tax deals with developing countries|url =https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/feb/23/uk-tops-global-table-of-damaging-tax-deals-with-developing\u2013countries|work=The Guardian|date=23 February 2016}}</ref> The \"blacklisting\" of a corporate tax haven is a serious event, which is why major BEPS hubs are OECD-compliant. Ireland was the first major corporate tax haven to be \"blacklisted\" by a G20 economy: Brazil in September 2016.<ref name=\"reuters1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/ireland-brazil-funds/blacklisted-by-brazil-dublin-funds-find-new-ways-to-invest-idUSL8N1MK2NX|title=Blacklisted by Brazil, Dublin funds find new ways to invest|agency=Reuters|date=20 March 2017|newspaper=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.taxjustice.net/2017/04/10/tax-haven-blacklisting-13-latin-american-countries/|title=Tax haven blacklisting in Latin America|publisher=Tax Justice Network|date=6 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nAn important academic study in July 2017 published in ''[[Nature (Magazine)|Nature]]'', \"[[Conduit and Sink OFCs]]\", showed that the pressure to maintain OECD\u2013compliance had split corporate\u2013focused tax havens into two different classifications: [[Conduit and Sink OFCs#Sink OFC|Sink OFCs]], which act as the ''terminus'' for BEPS flows, and [[Conduit and Sink OFCs#Conduit OFC|Conduit OFCs]], which act as the ''conduit'' for flows from higher\u2013tax locations to the Sink OFCs. It was noted that the five major Conduit OFCs, namely, Ireland, the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, Singapore and Switzerland, all have a top\u2013ten ranking in the 2018 ''[[Global Intellectual Property Center|Global Innovation Property Centre]] (GIPC) IP Index\".<ref name=\"ip\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theglobalipcenter.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/GIPC_IP_Index_2018.pdf|title=GIPC IP Index 2018|date=February 2018|author=United States Chamber of Commerce|quote=Figure I: U.S. Chamber International IP Index 2018, Overall Scores|page=6|author-link=United States Chamber of Commerce}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pre-Tax Profits of U.S. foreign subsidiaries (2015 BEA Data).jpg|thumb|upright=1.6|Profitability of U.S. subsidiaries (2015 [[Bureau of Economic Analysis|BEA]] data).<ref name=\"gabrielzucman\"/>]]\n\nOnce profits are \"shifted\" to the corporate tax haven (or Conduit OFC), additional tools are used to avoid paying ''headline'' tax rates in the haven. Some of the tools are OCED\u2013compliant (e.g. [[patent box]]es, [[double Irish arrangement#Backstop of capital allowances|Capital Allowances for Intangible Assets]] (\"CAIA\") or \"[[Ireland as a tax haven#Green Jersey|Green Jersey]]\"), others became OECD\u2013proscribed (e.g. [[Double Irish]] and [[Corporate haven#Dutch \"Double Dip\"|Dutch Double\u2013Dipping]]), while others have not attracted OECD attention (e.g. [[double Irish arrangement#Replacement by single malt|Single Malt]]).\n\nBecause BEPS hubs (or Conduit OFCs) need extensive bilateral [[tax treaties]] (e.g. so that their BEPS tools will be accepted by the higher\u2013tax locations), they go to great lengths to obscure the fact that ''effective tax rates'' paid by multinationals in their jurisdiction are close to zero percent, rather than the ''headline'' corporate tax rate of the haven (see [[#Table 1|Table 1]]). Higher\u2013tax jurisdictions do not enter into full bilateral tax treaties with obvious tax havens (e.g. the Cayman Islands, a major Sink OFC). That is achieved with [[Financial Secrecy Index|financial secrecy]] laws, and by the avoidance of ''country\u2013by\u2013country reporting'' (\"CbCr\") or the need to file public accounts, by multinationals in the haven's jurisdiction. BEPS hubs (or Conduit OFCs) strongly deny they are corporate tax havens, and that their use of IP is as a tax avoidance tool.<ref name=\"straits\">{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/banking/spore-is-no-tax-haven-govt-experts-here|title=MOF rejects claim of Singapore as tax haven|work=The Straits Times|date=14 December 2016}}</ref> They call themselves \"[[Corporate haven#The \"Knowledge Economy\"|knowledge economies]]\".<ref name=\"sing\">{{Cite web|title=Singapore's government says it's not a tax haven, it's a value-adding IP hub|url = https://www.smh.com.au/business/singapores-government-says-its-not-a-tax-haven-its-a-valueadding-hub-20150430-1mwvdu.html|work=Sydney Morning Hearald|date=30 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Make no mistake: the headline rate is not what triggers tax evasion and aggressive tax planning. That comes from schemes that facilitate profit shifting.|source=[[Pierre Moscovici]], EU Commissioner on Taxation, Financial Times, 11 March 2018<ref name=\"pierre\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/2b356956-17fc-11e8-9376-4a6390addb44|title=Multinationals pay lower taxes than a decade ago|work=Financial Times|date=11 March 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nThe complex accounting tools, and the detailed tax legislation, that corporate tax havens require to become OECD\u2013compliant BEPS hubs, requires both advanced international tax\u2013law professional services firms, and a high degree of coordination with the State, who encode their BEPS tools into the State's statutory legislation.<ref name=\"oxf\">{{cite web | url=https://maketaxfair.net/decorrespondent-reveals-netherlands-became-tax-haven/| title=DE CORRESPONDENT REVEALS HOW THE NETHERLANDS BECAME TAX HAVEN|publisher=Oxfam/De Correspondant|date=May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"dut5\">{{Cite web|title = The Professionals: Dealing with the enablers of tax avoidance and financial crime|url = https://www.taxjustice.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/The-Enablers-of-Tax-Avoidance-TJN-Briefing.pdf|publisher=[[Tax Justice Network]]|date=November 2017|author=George Turner}}</ref> Tax investigators call such jurisdictions \"[[Ireland as a tax haven#Captured state|captured states]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2011/jan/09/explainer-what-is-tax-haven|quote=This political capture produces one of the great offshore paradoxes: these zones of ultra\u2013freedom are often highly repressive places, wary of scrutiny and intolerant of criticism.|title=Explainer: what is a tax haven? The most important feature of a secrecy jurisdiction is that local politics is captured by financial services interests|work=The Guardian|date=9 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.taxjustice.net/tag/captured-state/|title=Tax Justice Network: Captured State|publisher=Tax Justice Network|date=November 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"amzn\">{{Cite web|title=Revealed: Project Goldcrest, how Amazon worked with the Luxembourg Government to avoid huge sums in tax with IP|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/feb/18/revealed-project-goldcrest-amazon-avoid-huge-sums-tax|work=The Guardian|date=18 February 2016}}</ref> and explain that most leading BEPS hubs started as established [[financial centres]], where the necessary skills and State support for tax avoidance tools, already existed.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Tax haven networks and the role of the Big 4 accountancy firms|author1=Alex Cobham|author2=Chris Jones|author3=Yama Temouri|url=https://www.taxjustice.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/JWB-Big-4-Jones-Temouri-Cobham-2017.pdf|journal=Journal of World Business|quote=Our key findings demonstrate that there is a strong correlation and causal link between the size of an MNE\u2019s tax haven network and their use of the Big 4|year=2017}}</ref><ref name=\"dut4\">{{Cite web|title=How Ireland became an offshore financial centre|url = https://www.taxjustice.net/2015/11/11/how-ireland-became-an-offshore-financial-centre/|author=Nicholas Shaxson|publisher=[[Tax Justice Network]]|date=November 2015|author-link = Nicholas Shaxson}}</ref>\n\n==Agendas{{anchor|Complex agendas}}==\n{{main|Ireland as a tax haven#Political compromises}}\n{{see also|Tax haven#Benefits of tax havens}}\n\nThe BEPS tools used by tax havens have been known and discussed for decades in Washington.<ref name=\"congress1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gao.gov/assets/290/284522.pdf|title=INTERNATIONAL TAXATION: Large U.S. Corporations and Federal Contractors with Subsidiaries in Jurisdictions Listed as Tax Havens or Financial Privacy Jurisdictions|publisher=U.S. GAO |quote=Table 1: Jurisdictions Listed as Tax Havens or Financial Privacy Jurisdictions and the Sources of Those Jurisdictions | page=12 | date=18 December 2008}}</ref> For example, when Ireland was pressured by the EU\u2013OECD to close its double Irish BEPS tool, the largest in history, to new entrants in January 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/ba95cff0-4fcd-11e4-a0a4-00144feab7de | title=Brussels in crackdown on 'double Irish' tax loophole| work=Financial Times| date=October 2014}}</ref> existing users, which include Google and Facebook, were given a five-year extension to 2020.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/irelands-move-to-close-the-double-irish-tax-loophole-unlikely-to-bother-apple-google-33011 | title=Ireland's move to close the 'double Irish' tax loophole unlikely to bother Apple, Google| work=The Guardian| date=October 2014}}</ref> Even before 2015, Ireland had already publicly replaced the double Irish with two new BEPS tools: the single malt (as used by Microsoft and Allergan), and capital allowances for intangible assets (\"CAIA\"), also called the \"Green Jersey\", (as used by Apple in Q1 2015).<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Multinationals replacing 'Double Irish' with new tax avoidance scheme|journal = RT\u00c9.ie|url = https://www.rte.ie/news/business/2017/1114/919979-multinationals-using-new-arrangement-to-reduce-tax-bill/|date = 14 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = How often is the 'Single Malt' tax loophole used? The government is finding out|url = http://www.thejournal.ie/single-malt-tax-evasion-3698512-Nov2017/|website = thejournal.ie|date = 15 November 2017}}</ref> None of these new BEPS tools have been as yet proscribed by the OECD.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gabriel-zucman.eu/files/TWZ2017.pdf|title=\u20ac600 billion and counting: Why high-tax locations let tax havens flourish|date=November 2017|author1=Gabriel Zucman|author2=Thomas T\u00f8rsl\u00f8v|author3=Ludvig Wier|publisher=[[National Bureau of Economic Research]], Working Papers|author1-link=Gabriel Zucman}}</ref> Tax experts show that disputes between higher-tax jurisdictions and tax havens are very rare.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Policy Failure of High-Tax Countries|pages=44\u201349|url=http://gabriel-zucman.eu/files/TWZ2018Slides.pdf|publisher=[[National Bureau of Economic Research]], Working Papers|author1=Gabriel Zucman|author2=Thomas Torslov|author3=Ludvig Wier |date=June 2018|author1-link=Gabriel Zucman}}</ref>\n\nTax experts describe a more complex picture of an implicit acceptance by Washington that U.S. multinationals could use BEPS tools on non\u2013U.S. earnings to offset the very high U.S. 35% corporate tax rate from the historical U.S. \"worldwide\" corporate tax system (see [[Ireland as a tax haven#Source of contradictions|source of contradictions]]).<ref>{{cite journal|title=Tax havens: how globalization really works: Ronen Palan, Richard Murphy and Christian Chavagneux|journal=Journal of Economic Geography|volume=11|issue=4|pages=753\u2013756|author1=Ronen Palan|author2-link=Richard Murphy (tax campaigner)|author2=Richard Murphy|date=1 July 2011|doi=10.1093/jeg/lbr008|author1-link=Ronen Palan}}</ref> Other tax experts, including a founder of academic tax haven research, [[James R. Hines Jr.]], note that U.S. multinational use of BEPS tools and corporate tax havens had actually increased the long\u2013term tax receipts of the U.S. exchequer, at the expense of other higher\u2013tax jurisdictions, making the [[Tax haven#U.S. as the largest beneficiary|U.S a major beneficiary of BEPS tools and corporate-tax havens]].<ref name=\"h1\"/><ref name=\"dryng\">{{cite journal|title=Using Financial Accounting Data to Examine the Effect of Foreign Operations Located in Tax Havens and Other Countries on US Multinational Firms' Tax Rates|author1=Scott Dyreng|author2=Bradley P. Lindsey|date=12 October 2009|quote=Finally, we find that US firms with operations in some tax haven countries have higher federal tax rates on foreign income than other firms. This result suggests that in some cases, tax haven operations may increase US tax collections at the expense of foreign country tax collections.|journal=[[Journal of Accounting Research]]|volume = 47|issue=5|pages=1283\u20131316|doi=10.1111/j.1475-679X.2009.00346.x}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/special-report/2000/01/27/gimme-shelter|title=Gimme shelter - A survey of globalisation and tax|journal=[[The Economist]]|date=27 January 2000}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Lower foreign tax rates entail smaller credits for foreign taxes and greater ultimate U.S. tax collections (Hines and Rice, 1994).<ref name=\"h3\"/> Dyreng and Lindsey (2009),<ref name=\"dryng\"/> offer evidence that U.S. firms with foreign affiliates in certain tax havens pay lower pay lower foreign taxes and higher U.S. taxes than do otherwise-similar large U.S. companies.|author=[[James R. Hines Jr.]] |source=\"Treasure Islands\" p. 107 (2010)<ref name=\"h1\">{{cite journal|url=https://repository.law.umich.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=https://www.google.ie/&httpsredir=1&article=1716&context=articles|title=Treasure Islands|pages=103\u2013125|author=James R. Hines Jr.|quote=Lower foreign tax rates entail smaller credits for foreign taxes and greater ultimate U.S. tax collections (Hines and Rice, 1994). Dyreng and Lindsey (2009), offer evidence that U.S. firms with foreign affiliates in certain tax havens pay lower pay lower foreign taxes and higher U.S. taxes than do otherwise-similar large U.S. companies|journal=[[Journal of Economic Perspectives]]|volume=4|issue=24|date=2010|author-link=James R. Hines Jr}}</ref>}}\n\nThe [[James R. Hines Jr.#Tax haven research|1994 Hines\u2013Rice paper]]<ref name=\"h3\">{{cite journal|url=http://taxdoctoralseminar.web.unc.edu/files/2016/02/Hines-Rice.pdf|title=FISCAL PARADISE: FOREIGN TAX HAVENS AND AMERICAN BUSINESS|author1=James R. Hines Jr.|author2=Eric M. Rice|quote=We identify 41 countries and regions as tax havens for the purposes of U. S. businesses. Together the seven tax havens with populations greater than one million (Hong Kong, Ireland, Liberia, Lebanon, Panama, Singapore, and Switzerland) account for 80 percent of total tax haven population and 89 percent of tax haven GDP.|journal=Quarterly Journal of Economics (Harvard/MIT)|date=February 1994|volume=9|issue=1|access-date=8 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825172644/http://taxdoctoralseminar.web.unc.edu/files/2016/02/Hines-Rice.pdf|archive-date=25 August 2017|url-status=dead|author1-link=James R. Hines Jr}}</ref> on U.S. multinational use of tax havens was the first to use the term ''profit shifting''.<ref name=\"be\">{{cite web|url=https://chicagounbound.uchicago.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2385&context=law_and_economics|title=What Do We Know About Base Erosion and Profit Shifting? A Review of the Empirical Literature|publisher=[[University of Chicago]]|author=Dhammika Dharmapala|year=2014|quote= It focuses particularly on the dominant approach within the economics literature on income shifting, which dates back to Hines and Rice (1994) and which we refer to as the \u201cHines\u2013Rice\u201d approach.|page=1|author-link=Dhammika Dharmapala}}</ref> Hines\u2013Rice concluded, \"low foreign tax rates [from tax havens] ultimately enhance U.S. tax collections\".<ref name=\"h3\"/> For example, the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]] (\"TCJA\") levied 15.5% on the untaxed offshore cash reserves built up by U.S. multinationals with BEPS tools from 2004\u20132017. Had the U.S. multinationals not used BEPS tools and paid their full foreign taxes, their foreign tax credits would have removed most of their residual exposure to any U.S. tax liability, under the U.S. tax code.\n\nThe U.S. was one of the only major developed nations not to sign up to the 2016 {{slink|#OECD BEPS Project}} to curtail BEPS tools.<ref name=\"baker\"/>\n\n==Failure of OECD (2012\u20132016)==\n{{see also|Base erosion and profit shifting (OECD project)}}\nThe [[2012 G20 Los Cabos summit]] tasked the OECD to develop a ''BEPS Action Plan'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oecd.org/ctp/BEPSActionPlan.pdf|title=Action Plan on Base Erosion and Profit Shifting|publisher=OECD|year=2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oecd.org/ctp/beps.htm|title=Base Erosion and Profit Shifting|work=oecd.org}}</ref> which [[2013 G-20 St. Petersburg summit]] approved.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=St Petersburg Tax Annex OECD |date=September 2013 |url=http://www.mofa.go.jp/files/000013928.pdf |title=TAX ANNEX TO THE SAINT PETERSBURG G20 LEADERS DECLARATION}}</ref> The project is intended to prevent multinationals from shifting profits from higher- to lower-tax jurisdictions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blackline.com/blog/intercompany-accounting/whats-wrong-intercompany-accounting/|title=What's Wrong With Intercompany Accounting? Plenty.|date=2018-08-15|website=BlackLine Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-07}}</ref> An OECD BEPS [[Multilateral Convention to Implement Tax Treaty Related Measures to Prevent Base Erosion and Profit Shifting|Multilateral Instrument]], consisting of ''15 Actions'' designed to be implemented domestically and through bilateral tax treaty provisions, were agreed at the [[2015 G20 Antalya summit]].\n\nThe OECD BEPS Multilateral Instrument (\"MLI\"), was adopted on 24 November 2016 and has since been signed by over 78 jurisdictions. It came into force in July 2018. Many tax havens opted out from several of the Actions, including Action 12 (Disclosure of aggressive tax planning), which was considered onerous by corporations who use BEPS tools.\n\n[[File:Enda Kenny Feargal O'Rourke Taken at IBEC 2014 Conference Flickr.jpg|thumb|260px|Former Irish [[Taoiseach]] [[Enda Kenny]] (l), and PwC Partner [[Feargal O'Rourke]] (r) ''architect'' of two of the largest BEPS tools in the world, the [[Double Irish]] (including Microsoft, Google, Facebook, IBM, Johnson & Johnson and Pfizer, amongst many others), and the [[Ireland as a tax haven#Green Jersey|Green Jersey]] (as used by Apple in their Q1 2015 \"[[leprechaun economics]]\" restructuring in Ireland).<ref name=\"for0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-10-28/man-making-ireland-tax-avoidance-hub-globally-proves-local-hero| title=FEARGAL O'ROURKE: Man Making Ireland Tax Avoidance Hub Proves Local Hero | publisher=Bloomberg News|date=28 October 2013}}</ref>]]\n\n{{quote|Global legal firm [[Baker McKenzie]],<ref name=\"nytz\">{{Cite web| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/06/world/apple-taxes-jersey.html|quote=A key architect [for Apple] was [[Baker McKenzie]], a huge law firm based in Chicago. The firm has a reputation for devising creative offshore structures for multinationals and defending them to tax regulators. It has also fought international proposals for tax avoidance crackdowns.|title=After a Tax Crackdown, Apple Found a New Shelter for Its Profits | work = The New York Times|date=6 November 2017}}</ref> representing a coalition of 24 multinational US software firms, including Microsoft, lobbied [[Michael Noonan (Fine Gael politician)|Michael Noonan]], as [Irish] minister for finance, to resist the [OECD MLI] proposals in January 2017. In a letter to him the group recommended Ireland not adopt article 12, as the changes \u201cwill have effects lasting decades\u201d and could \u201champer global investment and growth due to uncertainty around taxation\u201d. The letter said that \u201ckeeping the current standard will make Ireland a more attractive location for a regional headquarters by reducing the level of uncertainty in the tax relationship with Ireland\u2019s trading partners\u201d.|author=[[Irish Times]]. \"Ireland resists closing corporation tax \u2018loophole\u2019\" (10 November 2017)<ref name=\"itm\">{{Cite web|author=Jack Power|title = Ireland resists closing corporation tax 'loophole'|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/ireland-resists-closing-corporation-tax-loophole-1.3286199|work=The Irish Times|date=10 November 2017}}</ref>}}\n\nThe acknowledged ''architect'' of the largest ever global corporate BEPS tools (e.g. Google and Facebooks' Double Irish and Apple's Green Jersey), tax partner [[Feargal O'Rourke]] from [[PriceWaterhouseCoopers]] (\"PwC), predicted in May 2015 that the OECD's MLI would be a success for the leading corporate tax havens, at the expense of the smaller, less developed, traditional [[tax havens]], whose BEPS tools were not sufficiently robust.<ref name=\"fer\">{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/financial-services/scion-of-a-prominent-political-dynasty-who-gave-his-vote-to-accountancy-1.2203820?mode=sample&auth-failed=1&pw-origin=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.irishtimes.com%2Fbusiness%2Ffinancial-services%2Fscion-of-a-prominent-political-dynasty-who-gave-his-vote-to-accountancy-1.2203820| title=Scion of a prominent political dynasty who gave his vote to accountancy| quote=Of the wider tax environment, O\u2019Rourke thinks the OECD base-erosion and profit-shifting (BEPS) process is \u201cvery good\u201d for Ireland: \"If BEPS sees itself to a conclusion, it will be good for Ireland.\"|work=The Irish Times|date=8 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, the [[Tax Justice Network]]'s Alex Cobham described the OECD's MLI as a failure due to the opt\u2013outs and watering\u2013down of individual BEPS Actions.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Alex |last1= Cobham |url=http://www.taxjustice.net/2016/08/24/us-treasury-tax-war-europe/ |quote=Second, it confirms (once again) that the OECD BEPS process has failed. |title=The US Treasury just declared tax war on Europe |date=24 August 2016 }}</ref> In December 2016, Cobham highlighted one of the key anti\u2013BEPS Actions, full public ''country\u2013by\u2013country\u2013reporting'' (\"CbCr\"), had been dropped due to lobbying by the U.S. multinationals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economia.icaew.com/news/december-2016/oecds-beps-measures-seriously-flawed|quote=The major problem, it says, has been the decision by the Organisation in 2013 when it came up with its standard on country\u2013by\u2013country reporting (CBCR) to give into intense lobbying, largely from US multinationals, and place limits on access to the data.|title=OECD's BEPs measures seriously flawed|publisher=economia|date=9 December 2016}}</ref> Country\u2013by\u2013country reporting is the only way to observe the level of BEPS activity and OECD compliance in any country conclusively .\n\nIn June 2017, a U.S. Treasury official explained that the reason why U.S. refused to sign up to the OECD's MLI, or any of its Actions, was because: \"the U.S. tax treaty network has a low degree of exposure to base erosion and profit shifting issues\".<ref name=\"baker\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bna.com/treasury-official-explains-n73014453413/ | title=Treasury Official Explains Why U.S. Didn't Sign OECD Super-Treaty | publisher=Bloomberg BNA | quote=The U.S. didn\u2019t sign the groundbreaking tax treaty inked by 68 [later 70] countries in Paris June 7 [2017] because the U.S. tax treaty network has a low degree of exposure to base erosion and profit shifting issues\", a U.S. Department of Treasury official said at a transfer pricing conference co\u2013sponsored by Bloomberg BNA and [[Baker McKenzie]] in Washington | date=8 June 2017 | access-date=8 August 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180522042953/https://www.bna.com/treasury-official-explains-n73014453413/ | archive-date=22 May 2018 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alston.com/en/insights/publications/2017/07/impact-of-mli-on-taxpayers|title=International Tax Advisory: Impact of the Multilateral Instrument on U.S. Taxpayers: Why Didn't the United States Choose to Sign the MLI?|publisher=[[Alston & Bird]]|date=14 July 2014|quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Failure of TCJA (2017\u20132018)==\n\n[[File:Ireland Trade Good Discrepancy (1995-2017).png|thumb|upright=1.4|Apple's Q1 2015 Irish quasi\u2013[[tax inversion]] of USD 300 billon in IP, is the largest [[BEPS]] transaction in history, and double the blocked 2016 USD 160 billion Pfizer\u2013Allergan Irish [[corporate inversion|inversion]].<ref name=\"cofr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cfr.org/blog/tax-avoidance-and-irish-balance-payments|title=Tax Avoidance and the Irish Balance of Payments|publisher=[[Council on Foreign Relations]]|author1=Brad Setser|author2=Cole Frank|date=25 April 2018|author1-link=Brad Setser}}</ref> Irish secrecy laws prevented the transaction from being confirmed until January 2018, and was labelled \"[[Leprechaun economics]]\" by Nobel Prize\u2013winning economist, [[Paul Krugman]].]]\n\n{{see also|Ireland as a tax haven#Impact of TCJA}}\n{{see also|Double Irish arrangement#Effect of Tax Cuts and Jobs Act}}\n\nThe [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]] (\"TCJA\") moved the U.S. from a \"worldwide\" corporate tax system to a hybrid{{efn|The TCJA system is described as ''hybrid'', because it still forces minimum U.S. tax rates on foreign income under the TCJA GILTI regime}} \"territorial\" tax system. The TCJA includes anti\u2013BEPS tool regimes including the GILTI\u2013tax and BEAT\u2013tax regimes. It also contains its own BEPS tools, namely the FDII\u2013tax regime.{{efn|The FDII regime allows U.S. multinationals to charge-out [[intellectual property]] (\"IP\") direct from the U.S., at a preferential 13.125% U.S. tax rate}} The TCJA could represent a major change in Washington's tolerance of U.S. multinational use of BEPS tools. Tax experts in early 2018 forecast the demise of the two major U.S. corporate tax havens, Ireland and Singapore, in the expectation that U.S. multinationals would no longer need foreign BEPS tools.<ref name=\"harvd\">{{cite web|url=https://harvardmagazine.com/2018/05/mihir-desai-tax-reform|title=Tax Reform: Round One|work=Harvard Magazine|author=Mihir A. Desai|date=June 2018|author-link=Mihir A. Desai}}</ref>\n\nHowever, by mid\u20132018, U.S. multinationals had not repatriated any BEPS tools,{{efn|This is not to be confused with the repatriation of the circa USD 1 trillion in offshore untaxed cash; these are the [[intellectual property]] (\"IP\") assets that U.S. multinationals house in locations like Ireland, which are the ''raw materials'' for the BEPS tools. A repatriation of a major U.S. multinational BEPS tool would cause reverse\u2013[[leprechaun economics]] events in various tax havens}} and the evidence is that they have increased exposure to corporate tax havens. In March\u2013May 2018, Google committed to doubling its office space in Ireland,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://amp.independent.ie/business/commercial-property/google-to-pay-over-115m-to-buy-treasury-building-37154126.html|title=Google, Facebook and Salesforce.com dramatically expand their Dublin office hubs|date=26 July 2018|work=Irish Independent}}</ref> while in June 2018 it was shown that Microsoft is preparing to execute Apple's Irish BEPS tool, the \"Green Jersey\" (see [[Ireland as a tax haven#Technical issues with TCJA|Irish experience post\u2013TCJA]]).<ref name=\"em\">{{cite web|url= https://www.businesspost.ie/news/irish-microsoft-firm-worth-100bn-ahead-merger-419721|title=Irish Microsoft firm worth $100bn ahead of merger|work=Sunday Business Post|date=24 June 2018}}</ref> In July 2018, an Irish tax expert [[Seamus Coffey]], forecasted a potential boom in U.S. multinationals on\u2013shoring their BEPS tools from the Caribbean to Ireland, and not to the U.S. as was expected after TCJA.<ref name=\"seamus coffey green jersey\">{{cite web|url=http://economic-incentives.blogspot.com/2018/07/when-can-we-expect-next-wave-of-ip.html|title=When can we expect the next wave of IP onshoring?|quote=IP onshoring is something we should be expecting to see much more of as we move towards the end of the decade. Buckle up!|author=[[Seamus Coffey]], [[Irish Fiscal Advisory Council]]|date=18 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, it was shown that the TCJA contains [[Ireland as a tax haven#Technical issues with TCJA|technical issues]] that incentivise these actions.<ref name=\"brook\">{{cite web|url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/up-front/2018/05/25/6-ways-to-fix-the-tax-system-post-tcja/|title=6 ways to fix the tax system post TCJA|author=Ben Harris|publisher=[[Brookings Institution]]|date=25 May 2018|author-link=Ben Harris (economist)}}</ref> For example, by accepting Irish tangible, and intangible, capital allowances in the GILTI calculation, Irish BEPS tools like the \"Green Jersey\" enable U.S. multinationals to achieve ''U.S. effective tax rates'' of 0\u20133% via the TCJA's foreign ''participation relief'' system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://taxfoundation.org/treatment-foreign-profits-tax-cuts-jobs-act/|publisher=[[Tax Foundation]]|date=3 May 2018|title=A Hybrid Approach: The Treatment of Foreign Profits under the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act}}</ref> There is debate as to whether they are drafting mistakes to be corrected or concessions to enable U.S. multinationals to reduce their effective corporate tax rates to circa 10% (the Trump administration's original target).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/79538ba6-a35b-11e7-b797-b61809486fe2|title=Donald Trump seeks to slash US corporate tax rate|date=27 September 2017|work=Financial Times|quote=Cutting the official corporate tax rate to 20 per cent from its present 35 per cent \u2014 a level that US companies say hurts them in global competition \u2014 would leave companies short of the 15 per cent Mr Trump promised as a candidate}}</ref>\n\n[[File:U.S. corporate profits booked in tax havens.png|thumb|upright=1.4|Distribution of U.S. corporate profits (as a % of U.S. GDP) booked in foreign locations (BEA Data).<ref name=\"brad1\"/>]]\n\nIn February 2019, [[Brad Setser]] from the [[Council on Foreign Relations]] (CoFR), wrote an article for ''[[The New York Times]]'' highlighting material issues with TCJA in terms of curtailing U.S. corporate use of major tax havens such as Ireland, the Netherlands, and Singapore.<ref name=\"brad1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/06/opinion/business-economics/trump-tax-reform-state-of-the-union-2019.html|title=The Global Con Hidden in Trump's Tax Reform Law, Revealed|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=[[Brad Setser]], [[Council on Foreign Relations]]|date=6 February 2019|accessdate=24 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nSetser followed up his New York Times piece on the CoFR website with:\n\n{{quote|So, best I can tell, neither the OECD\u2019s base erosion and profit shifting work nor the U.S. [TCJA] tax reform, will end the ability of major U.S. companies to reduce their overall tax burden by aggressively shifting profits offshore (and paying between 0-3 percent on their offshore profits and then being taxed at the GILTI 10.5 percent rate net of any taxes paid abroad and the deduction for tangible assets abroad). The only good news, as I see it, is that the scale of profit shifting is now so big that it almost cannot be ignored\u2014it is distorting the U.S. GDP numbers, not just the Irish numbers. And in my view, the current tax reform\u2019s failure to change the incentive to profit shift will eventually become so obvious that it will become clear that the reform itself needs to be reformed.|source=[[Brad Setser]], \"Why the U.S. Tax Reform's International Provisions Need to Be Reformed\", [[Council on Foreign Relations]], (2019).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cfr.org/blog/why-us-tax-reforms-international-provisions-need-be-reformed|title=Why the U.S. Tax Reform's International Provisions Need to Be Reformed|date=19 February 2019|accessdate=24 February 2019|author=Brad Setser|publisher=[[Council on Foreign Relations]]|author-link=Brad Setser}}</ref>}}\n\n==OECD BEPS 2.0 (2019){{anchor|BEPS 2.0}}==\n\nOn 29 January 2019, the OECD released a policy note regarding new proposals to combat the BEPS activities of multinationals, which commentators labeled \"BEPS 2.0\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.internationaltaxreview.com/Article/3857109/Why-BEPS-20-makes-tax-heads-nervous.html|title=Why BEPS 2.0 makes tax heads nervous|publisher=International Tax Review|date=4 February 2019|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://taxfoundation.org/beps-oecd-base-erosion-profit-shifting/|title=Ready to go on BEPS 2.0?|publisher=[[Tax Foundation]]|author=Daniel Bunn|date=14 February 2019|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref> In its press release, the OECD announced its proposals had the backing of the U.S., as well as China, Brazil, and India.<ref name=\"ref1\"/>\n\nIrish-based media highlighted a particular threat to Ireland as the world's largest BEPS hub, regarding proposals to move to a global system of taxation based on where the product is consumed or used, and not where its IP has been located.<ref name=\"ref1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/economy/ireland-may-soon-run-out-of-road-on-tax-1.3779223|title=Ireland may soon run out of road on tax|newspaper=[[Irish Times]]|author=Cantillion|date=2 February 2019|accessdate=26 February 2019|quote=In a policy note, the Washington-based think tank said US proposals to ensure companies pay taxes based on where they make their sales were gathering momentum and already had the backing of Brazil, China, India, and other emerging economies. Currently, the tax big companies such as Google and Facebook pay largely depends on where their assets, employees and head offices are located.}}</ref> The [[Institute of International and European Affairs|IIEA]] chief economist described the OECD proposal as \"a move last week [that] may bring the day of reckoning closer\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/opinion/comment/dan-obrien-as-brexit-gets-all-the-attention-changes-are-afoot-further-afield-37777296.html|title=Dan O'Brien: 'As Brexit gets all the attention, changes are afoot further afield'|newspaper=[[Irish Independent]]|author=Dan O'Brien|date=3 February 2019|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref> The Head of Tax for [[PwC]] in Ireland said, \"There's a limited number of [consumers] users in Ireland and [the proposal under consideration] would obviously benefit the much larger countries\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/business/irish/irish-corporation-tax-faces-new-squeeze-as-oecd-kicks-off-digital-reform-probe-37766815.html|title=Irish corporation tax faces new squeeze as OECD kicks off digital reform probe|newspaper=[[Irish Independent]]|date=31 January 2019|accessdate=26 February 2019|author=Gavin McLoughlin}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Tax haven]]\n*[[Conduit and Sink OFCs]]\n*[[James R. Hines Jr.]]\n*[[Gabriel Zucman]]\n*[[Ireland as a tax haven]]\n*[[Transfer mispricing]]\n\n==Notes==\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.oecd.org/tax/beps/ OECD BEPS Portal]\n* [https://www.ey.com/gl/en/services/tax/ey-beps-developments-tracker Ernst & Young BEPS Portal]\n* [https://home.kpmg.com/uk/en/home/services/tax/base-erosion-and-profit-shifting.html KPMG BEPS Portal]\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Globalization}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Base Erosion and Profit Shifting (BEPS)}}\n[[Category:Competition (economics)]]\n[[Category:International business]]\n[[Category:International taxation]]\n[[Category:Pricing]]\n[[Category:Tax avoidance]]\n[[Category:Corporate tax avoidance]]\n[[Category:Offshore finance]]\n[[Category:Corporate taxation in the United States]]\n[[Category:Global issues]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2018}}\n{{short description|Multinational tax avoidance tools}}\n\n{{Taxation}}\n\n[[File:Treasury Department rear view.JPG|thumb|The [[United States Department of the Treasury]] decided against signing the 2016 OECD anti\u2013BEPS MLI initiative from the {{slink|#OECD BEPS Project}}, stating that the U.S.: \"has a low degree of exposure to base erosion and profit shifting\".<ref name=\"baker\"/>\n International tax academics showed in 2018 that U.S. multinationals are the largest users of BEPS tools in the world;<ref name=\"zucwright\"/> while U.S tax academics demonstrated, even as early as 1994, that the U.S. exchequer is a net beneficiary from the use of tax havens and BEPS by U.S. multinationals.<ref name=\"h1\"/><ref name=\"dryng\"/>]]\n\n'''Base erosion and profit shifting''' ('''BEPS''') refers to corporate [[tax planning]] strategies used by [[multinational companies|multinationals]] to \"shift\" profits from higher-tax jurisdictions to lower-tax jurisdictions, thus \"eroding\" the \"tax-base\" of the higher-tax jurisdictions.<ref name=\"be\"/><ref name=\"oecd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oecd.org/tax/beps/|title=OECD Base Erosion and Profit Shifting}}</ref>\n\nThe [[OECD|Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] (OECD) define BEPS strategies as also \"exploiting gaps and mismatches in tax rules\";<ref name=\"oecd\"/> however, academics proved corporate [[tax havens]] (such as Ireland, the Caribbean, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Singapore, Switzerland, and Hong Kong),{{efn|These are also the largest [[offshore financial centres]] (\"OFCs\"); a term considered by academics to be synonymous with the term [[tax haven]]}} who are the largest [[Corporate haven#Global BEPS hubs|global BEPS hubs]], use OECD\u2013whitelisted tax structures and OECD\u2013compliant BEPS tools.<ref name=\"zux\"/><ref name=\"be\"/>\n\n[[Corporate tax haven]]s offer BEPS tools to \"shift\" profits to the haven, and additional BEPS tools to avoid paying taxes within the haven (e.g. Ireland's \"[[Ireland as a tax haven#Green Jersey|CAIA tool]]\").{{efn|The ''[[Capital Allowances for Intangible Assets]]'' (CAIA) BEPS tool, also known as the ''Green Jersey'', was the BEPS tool Apple used in Q1 2015 to restructure its non-U.S. IP. It created the famous \"[[leprechaun economics]]\" event in Ireland in August 2016, when restated Irish GDP rose 34.4% in a single quarter}} BEPS tools are associated mostly with U.S. [[technology]] and [[life science]] multinationals.{{efn|name=\"ip\"|The critical component of the most important BEPS tools is [[intellectual property]] (\"IP\"), which the BEPS tool converts into a charge that is deductible against pre\u2013tax income. Technology and Life Sciences industries have the largest pools of IP.}}<ref name=\"zucwright\"/> Tax academics showed use of the BEPS tools by U.S. multinationals, via [[tax havens]], maximised long\u2013term U.S. exchequer receipts and shareholder return, at the expense of others.<ref name=\"h1\"/><ref name=\"dryng\"/><ref name=\"zucwright\"/>\n\n==Scale==\nIn January 2017, the OECD estimated that BEPS tools are responsible for tax losses of circa $100\u2013240 billion per annum.<ref name=\"BEPS Background\">{{cite web|title=BEPS Project Background Brief| url=http://www.oecd.org/tax/beps/background-brief-inclusive-framework-for-beps-implementation.pdf|publisher=[[OECD]]|quote=With a conservatively estimated annual revenue loss of USD 100 to 240 billion, the stakes are high for governments around the world. The impact of BEPS on developing countries, as a percentage of tax revenues, is estimated to be even higher than in developed countries.|date=January 2017|page=9}}</ref> In June 2018, an investigation by tax academic [[Gabriel Zucman]] (et alia),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gabriel-zucman.eu/missingprofits/|title=The Missing Profits of Nations|quote=Appendix Table 2: Tax Havens|page=31|author1=Gabriel Zucman|author2=Thomas Torslov|author3=Ludvig Wier|publisher=[[National Bureau of Economic Research]], Working Papers|date=June 2018|author1-link=Gabriel Zucman}}</ref> estimated that the figure is closer to $200 billion per annum.<ref name=\"zuc10\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/corporations-push-profits-into-tax-havens-as-countries-struggle-in-pursuit-study-says-1528634659|title=Zucman:Corporations Push Profits Into Corporate Tax Havens as Countries Struggle in Pursuit, Gabrial Zucman Study Says|quote=Such profit shifting leads to a total annual revenue loss of $200 billion globally|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=10 June 2018}}</ref> The [[Tax Justice Network]] estimated that profits of $660 billion were \"shifted\" in 2015 (due to Apple's Q 2015 [[leprechaun economics]] restructuring, the largest individual BEPS transaction in history<ref name=\"cofr\"/>).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.taxjustice.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Tax-dodging-the-scale-of-the-problem-TJN-Briefing.pdf|title=Tax avoidance and evasion: The scale of the problem|publisher=[[Tax Justice Network]]|date=17 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The scale of Base Erosion and Profit Shifting (BEPS): Tax Justice Network|url=http://www.taxjustice.net/scalebeps/|website=[[Tax Justice Network]]}}</ref> The effect of BEPS tools is most felt in developing economies, who are denied the tax revenues needed to build infrastructure.<ref name=\"un1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.taxjustice.net/2017/09/11/new-un-tax-handbook-sets-lower-income-countries-oecd-beps/|title=New UN tax handbook: Lower\u2013income countries vs OECD BEPS failure|publisher=Tax Justice Network| date=11 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/nov/08/tax-havens-dodging-theft-multinationals-avoiding-tax|title=The desperate inequality behind global tax dodging|work=The Guardian| date=8 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nMost BEPS activity is associated with industries with [[intellectual property]] (\"IP\"), namely Technology (e.g. Apple, Google, Microsoft, Oracle), and Life Sciences (e.g. Allergan, Medtronic, Pfizer and Merck & Co) (see [[double Irish#US multinationals using Irish tax schemes|here]]).{{efn|name=\"ip\"}}<ref name=\"alex\">{{cite web|url=https://www.taxjustice.net/2018/07/24/progress-global-profit-shifting/|title=Progress on global profit shifting: no more hiding for jurisdictions that sell profit shifting at the expense of others|date=24 July 2018|author=Alex Cobham|quote=..for US multinationals, the real explosion in profit shifting began in the 1990s. At this point, a \u2018mere\u2019 5\u201310% of global profits were declared away from the jurisdictions of the underlying real economic activity. By the early 2010s, that had soared to 25\u201330% of global profits, with an estimated revenue loss of around $130 billion a year..|publisher=[[Tax Justice Network]]}}</ref> IP is described as the ''raw materials of tax avoidance'', and [[Corporate haven#IP-based BEPS tools|IP\u2013based BEPS tools]] are responsible for the largest global BEPS income flows.<ref name=\"ucla\">{{cite web | url=https://www.uclalawreview.org/pdf/62-1-1.pdf | title=Intellectual Property Law Solutions to Tax Avoidance | author=Andrew Blair-Stanek|quote=Intellectual property (IP) has become the leading tax-avoidance vehicle.| publisher=UCLA Law Review |year=2015}}</ref><ref name=\"fordam\">{{cite web | url=http://www.fordhamiplj.org/2016/08/30/ip-tax-avoidance-ireland/ | title=Intellectual Property and Tax Avoidance in Ireland | publisher=[[Fordham Intellectual Property, Media & Entertainment Law Journal]] | date=30 August 2016}}</ref> Corporate tax havens have some of the most [[Corporate haven#The \"Knowledge Economy\"|advanced IP tax leglislation]] in their statute books.<ref name=\"ip\"/>\n\nMost BEPS activity is also most associated with U.S. multinationals,<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/corporations-push-profits-into-tax-havens-as-countries-struggle-in-pursuit-study-says-1528634659|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|author= Richard Rubin|quote=U.S. companies are the most aggressive users of profit-shifting techniques, which often relocate paper profits without bringing jobs and wages, according to the study by economists Thomas Torslov and Ludvig Wier of the University of Copenhagen and Gabriel Zucman of the University of California, Berkeley|date=10 June 2018|title=Corporations Push Profits Into Tax Havens as Countries Struggle in Pursuit, Study Says}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nordic.businessinsider.com/new-research-finds-40-of-multinationals-profits-shifted-to-tax-havens--eu-biggest-loser-while-us-firms-most-shifty--/|website=[[Business Insider]]|title=New research finds 40% of multinationals' profits shifted to tax havens \u2013 EU biggest loser while US firms most shifty|date=20 July 2018|access-date=31 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831002541/https://nordic.businessinsider.com/new-research-finds-40-of-multinationals-profits-shifted-to-tax-havens--eu-biggest-loser-while-us-firms-most-shifty--/|archive-date=31 August 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"be\"/><ref name=\"alex\"/> and is attributed to the historical U.S. \"worldwide\" corporate taxation system.<ref name=\"be\"/><ref name=\"hines2016\">{{cite journal| url = https://repository.law.umich.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2831&context=articles|title=Multinational Firms and Tax Havens|author1=James R. Hines Jr.|author2=Anna Gumpert|author3=Monika Schnitzer|year=2016|journal=[[The Review of Economics and Statistics]]|page=714|quote=Germany taxes only 5% of the active foreign business profits of its resident corporations. [..] Furthermore, German firms do not have incentives to structure their foreign operations in ways that avoid repatriating income. Therefore, the tax incentives for German firms to establish tax haven affiliates are likely to differ from those of U.S. firms and bear strong similarities to those of other G-7 and OECD firms.|volume=98|issue=4|author1-link=James R. Hines Jr}}</ref> Pre the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]] (TCJA), the U.S. was one of only eight jurisdictions to operate a \"worldwide\" tax system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/wp/2013/wp13205.pdf|title=Territorial vs. Worldwide Corporate Taxation: Implications for Developing Countries|publisher=IMF|year=2013|page=4}}</ref> Most global jurisdictions operate a \"territorial\" corporate tax system with lower tax rates for foreign sourced income, thus avoiding the need to \"shift\" profits (i.e. IP can be charged directly from the home country at preferential rates and/or terms; post the 2017 TCJA, this happens in the U.S. via the FDII-regime).<ref name=\"uuu1\">{{cite web|url=https://files.taxfoundation.org/legacy/docs/TaxFoundation_FF442.pdf | title=Tax Reform in the UK Reversed the Tide of Corporate Tax Inversions | publisher=Tax Foundation| date=14 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"uk1\">{{cite web|url= https://taxfoundation.org/tax-reform-uk-reversed-tide-corporate-tax-inversions/|title=How Tax Reform solved UK inversions|publisher=Tax Foundation|date=14 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"uktax1\">{{cite web|url= https://taxfoundation.org/united-kingdom-s-experience-inversions/|title=The United Kingdom's Experience with Inversions|publisher=Tax Foundation|date=5 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|U.S. multinationals use tax havens{{efn|The paper lists tax havens as: ''Ireland, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Switzerland, Singapore, Bermuda and Caribbean havens'' (page 6.)}} more than multinationals from other countries which have kept their controlled foreign corporations regulations. No other non\u2013haven OECD country records as high a share of foreign profits booked in tax havens as the United States. [...] This suggests that half of all the global profits shifted to tax havens, are shifted by U.S. multinationals. By contrast, about 25% accrues to E.U. countries, 10% to the rest of the OECD, and 15% to developing countries (T\u00f8rsl\u00f8v et al., 2018).|source=[[Gabriel Zucman]], Thomas Wright, \"THE EXORBITANT TAX PRIVILEGE\", [[National Bureau of Economic Research|NBER]] Working Papers (September 2018).<ref name=\"zucwright\">{{cite journal|url=http://gabriel-zucman.eu/files/WrightZucman2018.pdf|title=THE EXORBITANT TAX PRIVILEGE|publisher=[[National Bureau of Economic Research]]|author1=Gabriel Zucman|page=11|author2=Thomas Wright|date=September 2018|author1-link=Gabriel Zucman}}</ref>}}\n\nResearch in June 2018 identified Ireland as the world's largest BEPS hub.<ref name=\"gabrielzucman\"/> Ireland is larger than the ''aggregate'' Caribbean tax haven BEPS system.<ref name=\"zux\">{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/economy/ireland-is-the-world-s-biggest-corporate-tax-haven-say-academics-1.3528401?mode=sample&auth-failed=1&pw-origin=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.irishtimes.com%2Fbusiness%2Feconomy%2Fireland-is-the-world-s-biggest-corporate-tax-haven-say-academics-1.3528401|title=Ireland is the world's biggest corporate 'tax haven', say academics|quote=New Gabriel Zucman study claims State shelters more multinational profits than the entire Caribbean|work=The Irish Times|date=13 June 2018}}</ref> The largest global BEPS hubs, from the [[Gabriel Zucman#Zucman-T\u00f8rsl\u00f8v-Wier 2018 list|Zucman\u2013T\u00f8rsl\u00f8v\u2013Wier]] table below, are synonymous with the [[Tax haven#Top 10 tax havens|top 10 global tax havens]]:\n{{anchor|Table 1}}\n[[File:Where do U.S. multinationals book their profits (2016 BEA).png|thumb|upright=1.6|U.S. multinationals book over half of their non\u2013U.S. profits in tax havens by using BEPS tools (2016 [[Bureau of Economic Analysis|BEA]]).<ref name=\"zucwright\"/><ref name=\"japantimes\"/>]]\n{| style=\"font-size:100%;\"\n|-\n| width=\"50%\" align=\"left\" |\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ style=\"text-align: left;\" | Zucman\u2013T\u00f8rsl\u00f8v\u2013Wier. ''Missing Profits of Nations''. Table 1: Shifted Profits (2015)<ref name=\"gabrielzucman\">{{cite web|url=http://gabriel-zucman.eu/|title=The Missing Profits of Nations|page=31|author1=Gabriel Zucman|author2=Thomas Torslov|author3=Ludvig Wier|quote=Table 2: Shifted Profits: Country\u2013by\u2013Country Estimates (2015)|publisher=[[National Bureau of Economic Research]], Working Papers|date=June 2018|author1-link=Gabriel Zucman}}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"background:#cfc;width:120px;text-align:left\" | Profits Shifted<br>(2015 $ bn)<ref name=\"gabrielzucman\"/>\n! style=\"width:190px;text-align:left\" | Jurisdiction\n! style=\"width:200px;text-align:left\" | Headline Corporate Tax Rate<br>(all firms) (%)\n! style=\"width:200px;text-align:left\" | Effective Corporate Tax Rate<br>(foreign firms) (%)<ref name=\"gabrielzucman\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"right\" | 106 || align=\"left\" | Ireland                  || align=\"right\" |  12.5 || align=\"right\" |  4 \n|-                                                                                                           \n| align=\"right\" |  97 || align=\"left\" | Caribbean\u2020 (ex. Bermuda) || align=\"right\" | <3    || align=\"right\" |  2  \n|-                                                                                                           \n| align=\"right\" |  70 || align=\"left\" | Singapore                || align=\"right\" |  17   || align=\"right\" |  8  \n|-                                                                                                           \n| align=\"right\" |  58 || align=\"left\" | Switzerland              || align=\"right\" |  21   || align=\"right\" | 16  \n|-                                                                                                           \n| align=\"right\" |  57 || align=\"left\" | Netherlands              || align=\"right\" |  25   || align=\"right\" | 10  \n|-                                                                                                           \n| align=\"right\" |  47 || align=\"left\" | Luxembourg               || align=\"right\" |  29   || align=\"right\" |  3  \n|-                                                                                                           \n| align=\"right\" |  39 || align=\"left\" | Hong Kong                || align=\"right\" |  18   || align=\"right\" | 18  \n|}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|}\n(\u2020) Mostly consists of The Cayman Islands and The British Virgin Islands\n\nResearch in September 2018, by the [[National Bureau of Economic Research]], using repatriation tax data from the TCJA, said that: \"In recent years, about half of the foreign profits of U.S. multinationals have been booked in tax haven affiliates, most prominently in Ireland (18%), Switzerland, and Bermuda plus Caribbean tax havens (8%\u20139% each).<ref name=\"zucwright\"/> One of the authors of this research was also quoted as saying, \"Ireland solidifies its position as the #1 tax haven.... U.S. firms book more profits in Ireland than in China, Japan, Germany, France & Mexico combined. Irish tax rate: 5.7%.\"<ref name=\"japantimes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2018/09/11/business/half-u-s-foreign-profits-booked-tax-havens-especially-ireland-paper/#.W5eRKkZKhPY|title=Half of U.S. foreign profits booked in tax havens, especially Ireland: NBER paper|publisher=[[The Japan Times]]|quote=\u201cIreland solidifies its position as the #1 tax haven,\u201d Zucman said on Twitter. \u201cU.S. firms book more profits in Ireland than in China, Japan, Germany, France & Mexico combined. Irish tax rate: 5.7%.\u201d|date=10 September 2018|newspaper=The Japan Times Online}}</ref>\n\n==Tools==\n{{main|Corporate haven#Global BEPS hubs}}\n\nResearch identifies three main BEPS techniques used for \"shifting\" profits to a [[corporate tax haven]] via OECD\u2013compliant BEPS tools:<ref name=\"zew\">{{cite web|url=http://ftp.zew.de/pub/zew-docs/dp/dp13078.pdf|title=Profit Shifting and \"Aggressive\" Tax Planning by Multinational Firms|publisher=[[Zentrum f\u00fcr Europ\u00e4ische Wirtschaftsforschung|Centre for European Economic Research]], (ZEW)|author1=Clemens Fuest|author2=Christoph Spengel|author3=Katharina Finke|author4=Jost Heckemeyer|author5=Hannah Nusser|date=15 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"tilburg\">{{cite web | url=http://arno.uvt.nl/show.cgi?fid=143915| title=Intellectual Property Tax Planning in the light of Base Erosion and Profit Shifting | publisher=University of Tilburg | date=June 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{ordered list|type=lower-roman\n|[[Corporate haven#IP-based BEPS tools|IP\u2013based BEPS tools]],{{efn|name=\"IP\"|Some academics consider IP\u2013based BEPS tools to be a subset of TP\u2013based BEPS tools (e.g. the corporate is transfer pricing the IP like any other product), however others consider IP to be a unique item (e.g. the IP is a ''virtual product'' whose value is decided internally by the corporation; it is more of an accounting invention rather than a tangible good), that it is a separate set.}} which enable the profits to be extracted via the cross\u2013border charge\u2013out of internal virtual IP assets (known as \"intergroup IP charging\"); and/or\n|[[Corporate haven#Debt-based BEPS tools|Debt\u2013based BEPS tools]], which enable the profits to be extracted via the cross\u2013border charge\u2013out artificially high interest (known as \"earnings stripping\"); and/or\n|[[TP\u2013based BEPS tools]],{{efn|name=\"IP\"}} shifts profits to the haven by asserting that a ''process'' performed in the haven (e.g., [[contract manufacturing]]), justifies a large increase in the [[Transfer pricing|transfer price]] (\"TP\") at which the finished product is charged\u2013out by the haven to higher\u2013tax jurisdictions.\n}}\n\nBEPS tools could not function if the corporate tax haven did not have a network of bilateral tax treaties that accept the haven\u2019s BEPS tools, which \"shift\" the profits to the haven. Modern corporate tax havens, which are the main global BEPS hubs, have extensive networks of bilateral tax treaties.<ref name=\"dhh\">{{cite journal| url=https://academic.oup.com/oxrep/article/24/4/661/547359#|title=What Problems and Opportunities are Created by Tax Havens?|author=Dhammika Dharmapala|journal=[[Oxford Review of Economic Policy]]|page=3|date=December 2008|volume=24|issue=4|author-link=Dhammika Dharmapala}}</ref> The U.K. is the leader with over 122, followed by the Netherlands with over 100.<ref name=\"ukx\">{{cite journal|title=The Tax Treaty Network of the United Kingdom|url =http://www.fieldtax.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/2013-9-ILT-247-The-Tax-Treaty-Network-of-the-United-Kingdom1.pdf|journal=International Taxation|volume=9|issue=13|quote=The United Kingdom has 122 bilateral, comprehensive, double taxation conventions in force. It remains the largest number of tax treaties of any one country in the world. The United Kingdom may no longer be the world leader in manufacturing cars, or in playing football... however we are still the leading country in the world in negotiating double taxation conventions.|author=Philip Baker OBE QC|date=September 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"ukx1\">{{Cite web|title = UK tops global table of damaging tax deals with developing countries|url =https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/feb/23/uk-tops-global-table-of-damaging-tax-deals-with-developing\u2013countries|work=The Guardian|date=23 February 2016}}</ref> The \"blacklisting\" of a corporate tax haven is a serious event, which is why major BEPS hubs are OECD-compliant. Ireland was the first major corporate tax haven to be \"blacklisted\" by a G20 economy: Brazil in September 2016.<ref name=\"reuters1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/ireland-brazil-funds/blacklisted-by-brazil-dublin-funds-find-new-ways-to-invest-idUSL8N1MK2NX|title=Blacklisted by Brazil, Dublin funds find new ways to invest|agency=Reuters|date=20 March 2017|newspaper=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.taxjustice.net/2017/04/10/tax-haven-blacklisting-13-latin-american-countries/|title=Tax haven blacklisting in Latin America|publisher=Tax Justice Network|date=6 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nAn important academic study in July 2017 published in ''[[Nature (Magazine)|Nature]]'', \"[[Conduit and Sink OFCs]]\", showed that the pressure to maintain OECD\u2013compliance had split corporate\u2013focused tax havens into two different classifications: [[Conduit and Sink OFCs#Sink OFC|Sink OFCs]], which act as the ''terminus'' for BEPS flows, and [[Conduit and Sink OFCs#Conduit OFC|Conduit OFCs]], which act as the ''conduit'' for flows from higher\u2013tax locations to the Sink OFCs. It was noted that the five major Conduit OFCs, namely, Ireland, the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, Singapore and Switzerland, all have a top\u2013ten ranking in the 2018 ''[[Global Intellectual Property Center|Global Innovation Property Centre]] (GIPC) IP Index\".<ref name=\"ip\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theglobalipcenter.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/GIPC_IP_Index_2018.pdf|title=GIPC IP Index 2018|date=February 2018|author=United States Chamber of Commerce|quote=Figure I: U.S. Chamber International IP Index 2018, Overall Scores|page=6|author-link=United States Chamber of Commerce}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pre-Tax Profits of U.S. foreign subsidiaries (2015 BEA Data).jpg|thumb|upright=1.6|Profitability of U.S. subsidiaries (2015 [[Bureau of Economic Analysis|BEA]] data).<ref name=\"gabrielzucman\"/>]]\n\nOnce profits are \"shifted\" to the corporate tax haven (or Conduit OFC), additional tools are used to avoid paying ''headline'' tax rates in the haven. Some of the tools are OCED\u2013compliant (e.g. [[patent box]]es, [[double Irish arrangement#Backstop of capital allowances|Capital Allowances for Intangible Assets]] (\"CAIA\") or \"[[Ireland as a tax haven#Green Jersey|Green Jersey]]\"), others became OECD\u2013proscribed (e.g. [[Double Irish]] and [[Corporate haven#Dutch \"Double Dip\"|Dutch Double\u2013Dipping]]), while others have not attracted OECD attention (e.g. [[double Irish arrangement#Replacement by single malt|Single Malt]]).\n\nBecause BEPS hubs (or Conduit OFCs) need extensive bilateral [[tax treaties]] (e.g. so that their BEPS tools will be accepted by the higher\u2013tax locations), they go to great lengths to obscure the fact that ''effective tax rates'' paid by multinationals in their jurisdiction are close to zero percent, rather than the ''headline'' corporate tax rate of the haven (see [[#Table 1|Table 1]]). Higher\u2013tax jurisdictions do not enter into full bilateral tax treaties with obvious tax havens (e.g. the Cayman Islands, a major Sink OFC). That is achieved with [[Financial Secrecy Index|financial secrecy]] laws, and by the avoidance of ''country\u2013by\u2013country reporting'' (\"CbCr\") or the need to file public accounts, by multinationals in the haven's jurisdiction. BEPS hubs (or Conduit OFCs) strongly deny they are corporate tax havens, and that their use of IP is as a tax avoidance tool.<ref name=\"straits\">{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/banking/spore-is-no-tax-haven-govt-experts-here|title=MOF rejects claim of Singapore as tax haven|work=The Straits Times|date=14 December 2016}}</ref> They call themselves \"[[Corporate haven#The \"Knowledge Economy\"|knowledge economies]]\".<ref name=\"sing\">{{Cite web|title=Singapore's government says it's not a tax haven, it's a value-adding IP hub|url = https://www.smh.com.au/business/singapores-government-says-its-not-a-tax-haven-its-a-valueadding-hub-20150430-1mwvdu.html|work=Sydney Morning Hearald|date=30 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Make no mistake: the headline rate is not what triggers tax evasion and aggressive tax planning. That comes from schemes that facilitate profit shifting.|source=[[Pierre Moscovici]], EU Commissioner on Taxation, Financial Times, 11 March 2018<ref name=\"pierre\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/2b356956-17fc-11e8-9376-4a6390addb44|title=Multinationals pay lower taxes than a decade ago|work=Financial Times|date=11 March 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nThe complex accounting tools, and the detailed tax legislation, that corporate tax havens require to become OECD\u2013compliant BEPS hubs, requires both advanced international tax\u2013law professional services firms, and a high degree of coordination with the State, who encode their BEPS tools into the State's statutory legislation.<ref name=\"oxf\">{{cite web | url=https://maketaxfair.net/decorrespondent-reveals-netherlands-became-tax-haven/| title=DE CORRESPONDENT REVEALS HOW THE NETHERLANDS BECAME TAX HAVEN|publisher=Oxfam/De Correspondant|date=May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"dut5\">{{Cite web|title = The Professionals: Dealing with the enablers of tax avoidance and financial crime|url = https://www.taxjustice.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/The-Enablers-of-Tax-Avoidance-TJN-Briefing.pdf|publisher=[[Tax Justice Network]]|date=November 2017|author=George Turner}}</ref> Tax investigators call such jurisdictions \"[[Ireland as a tax haven#Captured state|captured states]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2011/jan/09/explainer-what-is-tax-haven|quote=This political capture produces one of the great offshore paradoxes: these zones of ultra\u2013freedom are often highly repressive places, wary of scrutiny and intolerant of criticism.|title=Explainer: what is a tax haven? The most important feature of a secrecy jurisdiction is that local politics is captured by financial services interests|work=The Guardian|date=9 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.taxjustice.net/tag/captured-state/|title=Tax Justice Network: Captured State|publisher=Tax Justice Network|date=November 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"amzn\">{{Cite web|title=Revealed: Project Goldcrest, how Amazon worked with the Luxembourg Government to avoid huge sums in tax with IP|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/feb/18/revealed-project-goldcrest-amazon-avoid-huge-sums-tax|work=The Guardian|date=18 February 2016}}</ref> and explain that most leading BEPS hubs started as established [[financial centres]], where the necessary skills and State support for tax avoidance tools, already existed.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Tax haven networks and the role of the Big 4 accountancy firms|author1=Alex Cobham|author2=Chris Jones|author3=Yama Temouri|url=https://www.taxjustice.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/JWB-Big-4-Jones-Temouri-Cobham-2017.pdf|journal=Journal of World Business|quote=Our key findings demonstrate that there is a strong correlation and causal link between the size of an MNE\u2019s tax haven network and their use of the Big 4|year=2017}}</ref><ref name=\"dut4\">{{Cite web|title=How Ireland became an offshore financial centre|url = https://www.taxjustice.net/2015/11/11/how-ireland-became-an-offshore-financial-centre/|author=Nicholas Shaxson|publisher=[[Tax Justice Network]]|date=November 2015|author-link = Nicholas Shaxson}}</ref>\n\n==Agendas{{anchor|Complex agendas}}==\n{{main|Ireland as a tax haven#Political compromises}}\n{{see also|Tax haven#Benefits of tax havens}}\n\nThe BEPS tools used by tax havens have been known and discussed for decades in Washington.<ref name=\"congress1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gao.gov/assets/290/284522.pdf|title=INTERNATIONAL TAXATION: Large U.S. Corporations and Federal Contractors with Subsidiaries in Jurisdictions Listed as Tax Havens or Financial Privacy Jurisdictions|publisher=U.S. GAO |quote=Table 1: Jurisdictions Listed as Tax Havens or Financial Privacy Jurisdictions and the Sources of Those Jurisdictions | page=12 | date=18 December 2008}}</ref> For example, when Ireland was pressured by the EU\u2013OECD to close its double Irish BEPS tool, the largest in history, to new entrants in January 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/ba95cff0-4fcd-11e4-a0a4-00144feab7de | title=Brussels in crackdown on 'double Irish' tax loophole| work=Financial Times| date=October 2014}}</ref> existing users, which include Google and Facebook, were given a five-year extension to 2020.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/irelands-move-to-close-the-double-irish-tax-loophole-unlikely-to-bother-apple-google-33011 | title=Ireland's move to close the 'double Irish' tax loophole unlikely to bother Apple, Google| work=The Guardian| date=October 2014}}</ref> Even before 2015, Ireland had already publicly replaced the double Irish with two new BEPS tools: the single malt (as used by Microsoft and Allergan), and capital allowances for intangible assets (\"CAIA\"), also called the \"Green Jersey\", (as used by Apple in Q1 2015).<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Multinationals replacing 'Double Irish' with new tax avoidance scheme|journal = RT\u00c9.ie|url = https://www.rte.ie/news/business/2017/1114/919979-multinationals-using-new-arrangement-to-reduce-tax-bill/|date = 14 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = How often is the 'Single Malt' tax loophole used? The government is finding out|url = http://www.thejournal.ie/single-malt-tax-evasion-3698512-Nov2017/|website = thejournal.ie|date = 15 November 2017}}</ref> None of these new BEPS tools have been as yet proscribed by the OECD.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gabriel-zucman.eu/files/TWZ2017.pdf|title=\u20ac600 billion and counting: Why high-tax locations let tax havens flourish|date=November 2017|author1=Gabriel Zucman|author2=Thomas T\u00f8rsl\u00f8v|author3=Ludvig Wier|publisher=[[National Bureau of Economic Research]], Working Papers|author1-link=Gabriel Zucman}}</ref> Tax experts show that disputes between higher-tax jurisdictions and tax havens are very rare.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Policy Failure of High-Tax Countries|pages=44\u201349|url=http://gabriel-zucman.eu/files/TWZ2018Slides.pdf|publisher=[[National Bureau of Economic Research]], Working Papers|author1=Gabriel Zucman|author2=Thomas Torslov|author3=Ludvig Wier |date=June 2018|author1-link=Gabriel Zucman}}</ref>\n\nTax experts describe a more complex picture of an implicit acceptance by Washington that U.S. multinationals could use BEPS tools on non\u2013U.S. earnings to offset the very high U.S. 35% corporate tax rate from the historical U.S. \"worldwide\" corporate tax system (see [[Ireland as a tax haven#Source of contradictions|source of contradictions]]).<ref>{{cite journal|title=Tax havens: how globalization really works: Ronen Palan, Richard Murphy and Christian Chavagneux|journal=Journal of Economic Geography|volume=11|issue=4|pages=753\u2013756|author1=Ronen Palan|author2-link=Richard Murphy (tax campaigner)|author2=Richard Murphy|date=1 July 2011|doi=10.1093/jeg/lbr008|author1-link=Ronen Palan}}</ref> Other tax experts, including a founder of academic tax haven research, [[James R. Hines Jr.]], note that U.S. multinational use of BEPS tools and corporate tax havens had actually increased the long\u2013term tax receipts of the U.S. exchequer, at the expense of other higher\u2013tax jurisdictions, making the [[Tax haven#U.S. as the largest beneficiary|U.S a major beneficiary of BEPS tools and corporate-tax havens]].<ref name=\"h1\"/><ref name=\"dryng\">{{cite journal|title=Using Financial Accounting Data to Examine the Effect of Foreign Operations Located in Tax Havens and Other Countries on US Multinational Firms' Tax Rates|author1=Scott Dyreng|author2=Bradley P. Lindsey|date=12 October 2009|quote=Finally, we find that US firms with operations in some tax haven countries have higher federal tax rates on foreign income than other firms. This result suggests that in some cases, tax haven operations may increase US tax collections at the expense of foreign country tax collections.|journal=[[Journal of Accounting Research]]|volume = 47|issue=5|pages=1283\u20131316|doi=10.1111/j.1475-679X.2009.00346.x}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/special-report/2000/01/27/gimme-shelter|title=Gimme shelter - A survey of globalisation and tax|journal=[[The Economist]]|date=27 January 2000}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Lower foreign tax rates entail smaller credits for foreign taxes and greater ultimate U.S. tax collections (Hines and Rice, 1994).<ref name=\"h3\"/> Dyreng and Lindsey (2009),<ref name=\"dryng\"/> offer evidence that U.S. firms with foreign affiliates in certain tax havens pay lower pay lower foreign taxes and higher U.S. taxes than do otherwise-similar large U.S. companies.|author=[[James R. Hines Jr.]] |source=\"Treasure Islands\" p. 107 (2010)<ref name=\"h1\">{{cite journal|url=https://repository.law.umich.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=https://www.google.ie/&httpsredir=1&article=1716&context=articles|title=Treasure Islands|pages=103\u2013125|author=James R. Hines Jr.|quote=Lower foreign tax rates entail smaller credits for foreign taxes and greater ultimate U.S. tax collections (Hines and Rice, 1994). Dyreng and Lindsey (2009), offer evidence that U.S. firms with foreign affiliates in certain tax havens pay lower pay lower foreign taxes and higher U.S. taxes than do otherwise-similar large U.S. companies|journal=[[Journal of Economic Perspectives]]|volume=4|issue=24|date=2010|author-link=James R. Hines Jr}}</ref>}}\n\nThe [[James R. Hines Jr.#Tax haven research|1994 Hines\u2013Rice paper]]<ref name=\"h3\">{{cite journal|url=http://taxdoctoralseminar.web.unc.edu/files/2016/02/Hines-Rice.pdf|title=FISCAL PARADISE: FOREIGN TAX HAVENS AND AMERICAN BUSINESS|author1=James R. Hines Jr.|author2=Eric M. Rice|quote=We identify 41 countries and regions as tax havens for the purposes of U. S. businesses. Together the seven tax havens with populations greater than one million (Hong Kong, Ireland, Liberia, Lebanon, Panama, Singapore, and Switzerland) account for 80 percent of total tax haven population and 89 percent of tax haven GDP.|journal=Quarterly Journal of Economics (Harvard/MIT)|date=February 1994|volume=9|issue=1|access-date=8 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825172644/http://taxdoctoralseminar.web.unc.edu/files/2016/02/Hines-Rice.pdf|archive-date=25 August 2017|url-status=dead|author1-link=James R. Hines Jr}}</ref> on U.S. multinational use of tax havens was the first to use the term ''profit shifting''.<ref name=\"be\">{{cite web|url=https://chicagounbound.uchicago.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2385&context=law_and_economics|title=What Do We Know About Base Erosion and Profit Shifting? A Review of the Empirical Literature|publisher=[[University of Chicago]]|author=Dhammika Dharmapala|year=2014|quote= It focuses particularly on the dominant approach within the economics literature on income shifting, which dates back to Hines and Rice (1994) and which we refer to as the \u201cHines\u2013Rice\u201d approach.|page=1|author-link=Dhammika Dharmapala}}</ref> Hines\u2013Rice concluded, \"low foreign tax rates [from tax havens] ultimately enhance U.S. tax collections\".<ref name=\"h3\"/> For example, the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]] (\"TCJA\") levied 15.5% on the untaxed offshore cash reserves built up by U.S. multinationals with BEPS tools from 2004\u20132017. Had the U.S. multinationals not used BEPS tools and paid their full foreign taxes, their foreign tax credits would have removed most of their residual exposure to any U.S. tax liability, under the U.S. tax code.\n\nThe U.S. was one of the only major developed nations not to sign up to the 2016 {{slink|#OECD BEPS Project}} to curtail BEPS tools.<ref name=\"baker\"/>\n\n==Failure of OECD (2012\u20132016)==\n{{see also|Base erosion and profit shifting (OECD project)}}\nThe [[2012 G20 Los Cabos summit]] tasked the OECD to develop a ''BEPS Action Plan'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oecd.org/ctp/BEPSActionPlan.pdf|title=Action Plan on Base Erosion and Profit Shifting|publisher=OECD|year=2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oecd.org/ctp/beps.htm|title=Base Erosion and Profit Shifting|work=oecd.org}}</ref> which [[2013 G-20 St. Petersburg summit]] approved.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=St Petersburg Tax Annex OECD |date=September 2013 |url=http://www.mofa.go.jp/files/000013928.pdf |title=TAX ANNEX TO THE SAINT PETERSBURG G20 LEADERS DECLARATION}}</ref> The project is intended to prevent multinationals from shifting profits from higher- to lower-tax jurisdictions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blackline.com/blog/intercompany-accounting/whats-wrong-intercompany-accounting/|title=What's Wrong With Intercompany Accounting? Plenty.|date=2018-08-15|website=BlackLine Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-07}}</ref> An OECD BEPS [[Multilateral Convention to Implement Tax Treaty Related Measures to Prevent Base Erosion and Profit Shifting|Multilateral Instrument]], consisting of ''15 Actions'' designed to be implemented domestically and through bilateral tax treaty provisions, were agreed at the [[2015 G20 Antalya summit]].\n\nThe OECD BEPS Multilateral Instrument (\"MLI\"), was adopted on 24 November 2016 and has since been signed by over 78 jurisdictions. It came into force in July 2018. Many tax havens opted out from several of the Actions, including Action 12 (Disclosure of aggressive tax planning), which was considered onerous by corporations who use BEPS tools.\n\n[[File:Enda Kenny Feargal O'Rourke Taken at IBEC 2014 Conference Flickr.jpg|thumb|260px|Former Irish [[Taoiseach]] [[Enda Kenny]] (l), and PwC Partner [[Feargal O'Rourke]] (r) ''architect'' of two of the largest BEPS tools in the world, the [[Double Irish]] (including Microsoft, Google, Facebook, IBM, Johnson & Johnson and Pfizer, amongst many others), and the [[Ireland as a tax haven#Green Jersey|Green Jersey]] (as used by Apple in their Q1 2015 \"[[leprechaun economics]]\" restructuring in Ireland).<ref name=\"for0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-10-28/man-making-ireland-tax-avoidance-hub-globally-proves-local-hero| title=FEARGAL O'ROURKE: Man Making Ireland Tax Avoidance Hub Proves Local Hero | publisher=Bloomberg News|date=28 October 2013}}</ref>]]\n\n{{quote|Global legal firm [[Baker McKenzie]],<ref name=\"nytz\">{{Cite web| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/06/world/apple-taxes-jersey.html|quote=A key architect [for Apple] was [[Baker McKenzie]], a huge law firm based in Chicago. The firm has a reputation for devising creative offshore structures for multinationals and defending them to tax regulators. It has also fought international proposals for tax avoidance crackdowns.|title=After a Tax Crackdown, Apple Found a New Shelter for Its Profits | work = The New York Times|date=6 November 2017}}</ref> representing a coalition of 24 multinational US software firms, including Microsoft, lobbied [[Michael Noonan (Fine Gael politician)|Michael Noonan]], as [Irish] minister for finance, to resist the [OECD MLI] proposals in January 2017. In a letter to him the group recommended Ireland not adopt article 12, as the changes \u201cwill have effects lasting decades\u201d and could \u201champer global investment and growth due to uncertainty around taxation\u201d. The letter said that \u201ckeeping the current standard will make Ireland a more attractive location for a regional headquarters by reducing the level of uncertainty in the tax relationship with Ireland\u2019s trading partners\u201d.|author=[[Irish Times]]. \"Ireland resists closing corporation tax \u2018loophole\u2019\" (10 November 2017)<ref name=\"itm\">{{Cite web|author=Jack Power|title = Ireland resists closing corporation tax 'loophole'|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/ireland-resists-closing-corporation-tax-loophole-1.3286199|work=The Irish Times|date=10 November 2017}}</ref>}}\n\nThe acknowledged ''architect'' of the largest ever global corporate BEPS tools (e.g. Google and Facebooks' Double Irish and Apple's Green Jersey), tax partner [[Feargal O'Rourke]] from [[PriceWaterhouseCoopers]] (\"PwC), predicted in May 2015 that the OECD's MLI would be a success for the leading corporate tax havens, at the expense of the smaller, less developed, traditional [[tax havens]], whose BEPS tools were not sufficiently robust.<ref name=\"fer\">{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/financial-services/scion-of-a-prominent-political-dynasty-who-gave-his-vote-to-accountancy-1.2203820?mode=sample&auth-failed=1&pw-origin=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.irishtimes.com%2Fbusiness%2Ffinancial-services%2Fscion-of-a-prominent-political-dynasty-who-gave-his-vote-to-accountancy-1.2203820| title=Scion of a prominent political dynasty who gave his vote to accountancy| quote=Of the wider tax environment, O\u2019Rourke thinks the OECD base-erosion and profit-shifting (BEPS) process is \u201cvery good\u201d for Ireland: \"If BEPS sees itself to a conclusion, it will be good for Ireland.\"|work=The Irish Times|date=8 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, the [[Tax Justice Network]]'s Alex Cobham described the OECD's MLI as a failure due to the opt\u2013outs and watering\u2013down of individual BEPS Actions.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Alex |last1= Cobham |url=http://www.taxjustice.net/2016/08/24/us-treasury-tax-war-europe/ |quote=Second, it confirms (once again) that the OECD BEPS process has failed. |title=The US Treasury just declared tax war on Europe |date=24 August 2016 }}</ref> In December 2016, Cobham highlighted one of the key anti\u2013BEPS Actions, full public ''country\u2013by\u2013country\u2013reporting'' (\"CbCr\"), had been dropped due to lobbying by the U.S. multinationals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economia.icaew.com/news/december-2016/oecds-beps-measures-seriously-flawed|quote=The major problem, it says, has been the decision by the Organisation in 2013 when it came up with its standard on country\u2013by\u2013country reporting (CBCR) to give into intense lobbying, largely from US multinationals, and place limits on access to the data.|title=OECD's BEPs measures seriously flawed|publisher=economia|date=9 December 2016}}</ref> Country\u2013by\u2013country reporting is the only way to observe the level of BEPS activity and OECD compliance in any country conclusively .\n\nIn June 2017, a U.S. Treasury official explained that the reason why U.S. refused to sign up to the OECD's MLI, or any of its Actions, was because: \"the U.S. tax treaty network has a low degree of exposure to base erosion and profit shifting issues\".<ref name=\"baker\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bna.com/treasury-official-explains-n73014453413/ | title=Treasury Official Explains Why U.S. Didn't Sign OECD Super-Treaty | publisher=Bloomberg BNA | quote=The U.S. didn\u2019t sign the groundbreaking tax treaty inked by 68 [later 70] countries in Paris June 7 [2017] because the U.S. tax treaty network has a low degree of exposure to base erosion and profit shifting issues\", a U.S. Department of Treasury official said at a transfer pricing conference co\u2013sponsored by Bloomberg BNA and [[Baker McKenzie]] in Washington | date=8 June 2017 | access-date=8 August 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180522042953/https://www.bna.com/treasury-official-explains-n73014453413/ | archive-date=22 May 2018 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alston.com/en/insights/publications/2017/07/impact-of-mli-on-taxpayers|title=International Tax Advisory: Impact of the Multilateral Instrument on U.S. Taxpayers: Why Didn't the United States Choose to Sign the MLI?|publisher=[[Alston & Bird]]|date=14 July 2014|quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Failure of TCJA (2017\u20132018)==\n\n[[File:Ireland Trade Good Discrepancy (1995-2017).png|thumb|upright=1.4|Apple's Q1 2015 Irish quasi\u2013[[tax inversion]] of USD 300 billon in IP, is the largest [[BEPS]] transaction in history, and double the blocked 2016 USD 160 billion Pfizer\u2013Allergan Irish [[corporate inversion|inversion]].<ref name=\"cofr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cfr.org/blog/tax-avoidance-and-irish-balance-payments|title=Tax Avoidance and the Irish Balance of Payments|publisher=[[Council on Foreign Relations]]|author1=Brad Setser|author2=Cole Frank|date=25 April 2018|author1-link=Brad Setser}}</ref> Irish secrecy laws prevented the transaction from being confirmed until January 2018, and was labelled \"[[Leprechaun economics]]\" by Nobel Prize\u2013winning economist, [[Paul Krugman]].]]\n\n{{see also|Ireland as a tax haven#Impact of TCJA}}\n{{see also|Double Irish arrangement#Effect of Tax Cuts and Jobs Act}}\n\nThe [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]] (\"TCJA\") moved the U.S. from a \"worldwide\" corporate tax system to a hybrid{{efn|The TCJA system is described as ''hybrid'', because it still forces minimum U.S. tax rates on foreign income under the TCJA GILTI regime}} \"territorial\" tax system. The TCJA includes anti\u2013BEPS tool regimes including the GILTI\u2013tax and BEAT\u2013tax regimes. It also contains its own BEPS tools, namely the FDII\u2013tax regime.{{efn|The FDII regime allows U.S. multinationals to charge-out [[intellectual property]] (\"IP\") direct from the U.S., at a preferential 13.125% U.S. tax rate}} The TCJA could represent a major change in Washington's tolerance of U.S. multinational use of BEPS tools. Tax experts in early 2018 forecast the demise of the two major U.S. corporate tax havens, Ireland and Singapore, in the expectation that U.S. multinationals would no longer need foreign BEPS tools.<ref name=\"harvd\">{{cite web|url=https://harvardmagazine.com/2018/05/mihir-desai-tax-reform|title=Tax Reform: Round One|work=Harvard Magazine|author=Mihir A. Desai|date=June 2018|author-link=Mihir A. Desai}}</ref>\n\nHowever, by mid\u20132018, U.S. multinationals had not repatriated any BEPS tools,{{efn|This is not to be confused with the repatriation of the circa USD 1 trillion in offshore untaxed cash; these are the [[intellectual property]] (\"IP\") assets that U.S. multinationals house in locations like Ireland, which are the ''raw materials'' for the BEPS tools. A repatriation of a major U.S. multinational BEPS tool would cause reverse\u2013[[leprechaun economics]] events in various tax havens}} and the evidence is that they have increased exposure to corporate tax havens. In March\u2013May 2018, Google committed to doubling its office space in Ireland,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://amp.independent.ie/business/commercial-property/google-to-pay-over-115m-to-buy-treasury-building-37154126.html|title=Google, Facebook and Salesforce.com dramatically expand their Dublin office hubs|date=26 July 2018|work=Irish Independent}}</ref> while in June 2018 it was shown that Microsoft is preparing to execute Apple's Irish BEPS tool, the \"Green Jersey\" (see [[Ireland as a tax haven#Technical issues with TCJA|Irish experience post\u2013TCJA]]).<ref name=\"em\">{{cite web|url= https://www.businesspost.ie/news/irish-microsoft-firm-worth-100bn-ahead-merger-419721|title=Irish Microsoft firm worth $100bn ahead of merger|work=Sunday Business Post|date=24 June 2018}}</ref> In July 2018, an Irish tax expert [[Seamus Coffey]], forecasted a potential boom in U.S. multinationals on\u2013shoring their BEPS tools from the Caribbean to Ireland, and not to the U.S. as was expected after TCJA.<ref name=\"seamus coffey green jersey\">{{cite web|url=http://economic-incentives.blogspot.com/2018/07/when-can-we-expect-next-wave-of-ip.html|title=When can we expect the next wave of IP onshoring?|quote=IP onshoring is something we should be expecting to see much more of as we move towards the end of the decade. Buckle up!|author=[[Seamus Coffey]], [[Irish Fiscal Advisory Council]]|date=18 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, it was shown that the TCJA contains [[Ireland as a tax haven#Technical issues with TCJA|technical issues]] that incentivise these actions.<ref name=\"brook\">{{cite web|url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/up-front/2018/05/25/6-ways-to-fix-the-tax-system-post-tcja/|title=6 ways to fix the tax system post TCJA|author=Ben Harris|publisher=[[Brookings Institution]]|date=25 May 2018|author-link=Ben Harris (economist)}}</ref> For example, by accepting Irish tangible, and intangible, capital allowances in the GILTI calculation, Irish BEPS tools like the \"Green Jersey\" enable U.S. multinationals to achieve ''U.S. effective tax rates'' of 0\u20133% via the TCJA's foreign ''participation relief'' system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://taxfoundation.org/treatment-foreign-profits-tax-cuts-jobs-act/|publisher=[[Tax Foundation]]|date=3 May 2018|title=A Hybrid Approach: The Treatment of Foreign Profits under the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act}}</ref> There is debate as to whether they are drafting mistakes to be corrected or concessions to enable U.S. multinationals to reduce their effective corporate tax rates to circa 10% (the Trump administration's original target).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/79538ba6-a35b-11e7-b797-b61809486fe2|title=Donald Trump seeks to slash US corporate tax rate|date=27 September 2017|work=Financial Times|quote=Cutting the official corporate tax rate to 20 per cent from its present 35 per cent \u2014 a level that US companies say hurts them in global competition \u2014 would leave companies short of the 15 per cent Mr Trump promised as a candidate}}</ref>\n\n[[File:U.S. corporate profits booked in tax havens.png|thumb|upright=1.4|Distribution of U.S. corporate profits (as a % of U.S. GDP) booked in foreign locations (BEA Data).<ref name=\"brad1\"/>]]\n\nIn February 2019, [[Brad Setser]] from the [[Council on Foreign Relations]] (CoFR), wrote a ''[[New York Times]]'' article highlighting material issues with TCJA in terms of curtailing U.S. corporate use of major tax havens such as Ireland, the Netherlands, and Singapore.<ref name=\"brad1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/06/opinion/business-economics/trump-tax-reform-state-of-the-union-2019.html|title=The Global Con Hidden in Trump's Tax Reform Law, Revealed|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|author=[[Brad Setser]], [[Council on Foreign Relations]]|date=6 February 2019|accessdate=24 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nSetser followed up his New York Times piece on the CoFR website with:\n\n{{quote|So, best I can tell, neither the OECD\u2019s base erosion and profit shifting work nor the U.S. [TCJA] tax reform, will end the ability of major U.S. companies to reduce their overall tax burden by aggressively shifting profits offshore (and paying between 0-3 percent on their offshore profits and then being taxed at the GILTI 10.5 percent rate net of any taxes paid abroad and the deduction for tangible assets abroad). The only good news, as I see it, is that the scale of profit shifting is now so big that it almost cannot be ignored\u2014it is distorting the U.S. GDP numbers, not just the Irish numbers. And in my view, the current tax reform\u2019s failure to change the incentive to profit shift will eventually become so obvious that it will become clear that the reform itself needs to be reformed.|source=[[Brad Setser]], \"Why the U.S. Tax Reform's International Provisions Need to Be Reformed\", [[Council on Foreign Relations]], (2019).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cfr.org/blog/why-us-tax-reforms-international-provisions-need-be-reformed|title=Why the U.S. Tax Reform's International Provisions Need to Be Reformed|date=19 February 2019|accessdate=24 February 2019|author=Brad Setser|publisher=[[Council on Foreign Relations]]|author-link=Brad Setser}}</ref>}}\n\n==OECD BEPS 2.0 (2019){{anchor|BEPS 2.0}}==\n\nOn 29 January 2019, the OECD released a policy note regarding new proposals to combat the BEPS activities of multinationals, which commentators labeled \"BEPS 2.0\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.internationaltaxreview.com/Article/3857109/Why-BEPS-20-makes-tax-heads-nervous.html|title=Why BEPS 2.0 makes tax heads nervous|publisher=International Tax Review|date=4 February 2019|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://taxfoundation.org/beps-oecd-base-erosion-profit-shifting/|title=Ready to go on BEPS 2.0?|publisher=[[Tax Foundation]]|author=Daniel Bunn|date=14 February 2019|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref> In its press release, the OECD announced its proposals had the backing of the U.S., as well as China, Brazil, and India.<ref name=\"ref1\"/>\n\nIrish-based media highlighted a particular threat to Ireland as the world's largest BEPS hub, regarding proposals to move to a global system of taxation based on where the product is consumed or used, and not where its IP has been located.<ref name=\"ref1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/economy/ireland-may-soon-run-out-of-road-on-tax-1.3779223|title=Ireland may soon run out of road on tax|newspaper=[[Irish Times]]|author=Cantillion|date=2 February 2019|accessdate=26 February 2019|quote=In a policy note, the Washington-based think tank said US proposals to ensure companies pay taxes based on where they make their sales were gathering momentum and already had the backing of Brazil, China, India, and other emerging economies. Currently, the tax big companies such as Google and Facebook pay largely depends on where their assets, employees and head offices are located.}}</ref> The [[Institute of International and European Affairs|IIEA]] chief economist described the OECD proposal as \"a move last week [that] may bring the day of reckoning closer\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/opinion/comment/dan-obrien-as-brexit-gets-all-the-attention-changes-are-afoot-further-afield-37777296.html|title=Dan O'Brien: 'As Brexit gets all the attention, changes are afoot further afield'|newspaper=[[Irish Independent]]|author=Dan O'Brien|date=3 February 2019|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref> The Head of Tax for [[PwC]] in Ireland said, \"There's a limited number of [consumers] users in Ireland and [the proposal under consideration] would obviously benefit the much larger countries\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/business/irish/irish-corporation-tax-faces-new-squeeze-as-oecd-kicks-off-digital-reform-probe-37766815.html|title=Irish corporation tax faces new squeeze as OECD kicks off digital reform probe|newspaper=[[Irish Independent]]|date=31 January 2019|accessdate=26 February 2019|author=Gavin McLoughlin}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Tax haven]]\n*[[Conduit and Sink OFCs]]\n*[[James R. Hines Jr.]]\n*[[Gabriel Zucman]]\n*[[Ireland as a tax haven]]\n*[[Transfer mispricing]]\n\n==Notes==\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.oecd.org/tax/beps/ OECD BEPS Portal]\n* [https://www.ey.com/gl/en/services/tax/ey-beps-developments-tracker Ernst & Young BEPS Portal]\n* [https://home.kpmg.com/uk/en/home/services/tax/base-erosion-and-profit-shifting.html KPMG BEPS Portal]\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Globalization}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Base Erosion and Profit Shifting (BEPS)}}\n[[Category:Competition (economics)]]\n[[Category:International business]]\n[[Category:International taxation]]\n[[Category:Pricing]]\n[[Category:Tax avoidance]]\n[[Category:Corporate tax avoidance]]\n[[Category:Offshore finance]]\n[[Category:Corporate taxation in the United States]]\n[[Category:Global issues]]\n", "name_user": "Alaney2k", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFailure of TCJA (2017\u20132018):the work's name is \"The New York Times\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Base_erosion_and_profit_shifting"}
{"title_page": "Greenacre Academy", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name          = Greenacre Academy\n| image         = \n| image_size          = \n| logo = File:Fair use logo Greenacre Academy.png \n| caption       = \n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.3507|0.5256|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto         = \n| established   =  \n| closed        = \n| type          = Secondary Modern (non-selective)<ref name=\"Ofsted Report 2018\"/> [[Academy (English school)|Academy]] \n| trust         = [https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/Groups/Group/Details/3243 Skills for life trust]  UID: 3243\n| religious_affiliation      = \n| president     = \n| head_label    =  \n| head          =  Mrs S Bridger\n| r_head_label  = \n| r_head        = \n| chair_label   = \n| chair         = \n| founder       = \n| address        = 157 Walderslade Road\n| city          = [[Walderslade]]\n| county        = [[Kent]]\n| country       = [[England]]\n| postcode      = ME5 0LP\n| dfeno         = 887/4174\n| urn           = 138046\n| ofsted        = yes\n| capacity      =\n| enrolment    = 913 {{As of|2015|12|lc=on}}\n| gender        = Boys\n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 18\n| houses        = \n| colours       =   \n| publication   = \n| free_label_1  = \n| free_1        = \n| free_label_2  = \n| free_2        = \n| free_label_3  = \n| free_3        = \n| website       = {{url|www.sflt.org.uk/greenacre/}}\n| module ={{OSM Location map\n | float = centre\n | width = 250\n | coord = {{coord|51.3729|0.5251}} <!-- Centred -->\n | mark-coord = {{coord|51.3507|0.5256}} | label = Greenacre School| label-pos = bottom |label-offset-x = 0\n | zoom = 12}} <!-- marking the school-->\n}}\n\n'''Greenacre Academy''' (formerly Greenacre School and before that Walderslade Boys School), is a boys' [[secondary school]] with shared [[sixth form]] located in [[Walderslade]] in the [[English county]] of [[Kent]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.school-portal.co.uk/GroupHomepage.asp?GroupId=326530 |title=Greenacre Academy ** |publisher=School-portal.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2013-12-14}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Medway Council|Medway]], as a former part of Kent retains selection, so Walderslade Boys School opened as a [[Secondary Modern]], taking the boys who had been deemed unacademic. Students in Medway must still take an eleven plus exam, and the more able students are creamed off to one of several grammar schools. Kent and Medway euphemistically call these 'high schools' It had the status of an 11-18\n[[Community school (England and Wales)|community school]] <ref name=\"Ofsted Report 2011\">{{cite web |title=Ofsted Report 2011 |url=https://files.ofsted.gov.uk/v1/file/1967157 |website=ofsted.gov.uk |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> school converted to [[Academy (English school)|academy status]] on 1 April 2012 and was renamed '''Greenacre Academy'''.\n<ref name=\"GIAS 2020\">{{cite web |title=Greenacre Academy - GOV.UK |url=https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/Establishments/Establishment/Details/138046 |website=get-information-schools.service.gov.uk |accessdate=2 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nIt was previously a [[Community school (England and Wales)|community school]] administered by [[Medway Council]]; the school converted to [[Academy (English school)|academy status]] on 1 April 2012 and was renamed Greenacre Academy. The school continues to coordinate with Medway Council for admissions.<ref name=\"GIAS 2020\"/>\n\nIt is part of the [[Skills for life trust]], which contains: '''Greenacre Academy''', [[Walderslade Girls School]], Warren Wood Primary Academy, Chantry Community Academy, Hilltop Primary Academy, Kloisters Kindergarten and Pre-School, PGW Sixth Form and Greenacre Sports Partnership.<ref name=\"SKILLS FOR LIFE TRUST\">{{cite web |title=SKILLS FOR LIFE TRUST - GOV.UK |url=https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/Groups/Group/Details/3243#list |website=get-information-schools.service.gov.uk |accessdate=1 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nOfsted rated this as a \u01f4ood School in 2014 and 2018. The school is strong in establishing good behaviour as one of its 'Skills for Life'. Pupils enter the school with lower than average literacy skills which are targetted.<ref name=\"Ofsted Report 2018\">{{cite web |title=Ofsted Report 2018 |url=https://files.ofsted.gov.uk/v1/file/2780689 |website=ofsted.gov.uk |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe school offers a three-year [[Key Stage 3]] where the core subjects of the National Curriculum are taught.<ref name=\"Website-KS3-4-and-5\">{{cite web |title=Website-KS3-4-and-5 |url=http://www.sflt.org.uk/greenacre/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2016/09/Website-KS3-4-and-5.pdf |website=www.sflt.org.uk/greenacre |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt [[Key Stage 4]], the academy offers [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSEs]], [[Business and Technology Education Council|BTECs]], [[OCR Nationals]] and [[National Vocational Qualification|NVQs]] as programmes of study for pupils. The subjects are English (Literature and Language), Maths, Science and Skills for Life. Students may study the English Baccalaureate as they are offered options of: Modern Foreign Languages, Computing and Humanities (History and Geography). Further choices are available to selected student.<ref name=\"Website-KS3-4-and-5\"/> Ofsted considers the rate of progress for students at the lower end is good, but the higher ability pupils underperform.<ref name=\"Ofsted Report 2018\"/>\n\nThe school also operates a sixth form provision in partnership with [[Walderslade Girls' School]], with students having the option to study from a range of [[GCE Advanced Level|A Levels]] and further BTECs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pgwsixthform.co.uk/ |title=PGW Sixth Form |publisher=PGW Sixth Form |date= |accessdate=2013-12-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214184130/http://www.pgwsixthform.co.uk/ |archive-date=14 December 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sflt.org.uk/greenacre/ Greenacre Academy Trust official website]\n\n{{Schools in Kent}}\n\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Medway]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in Kent]]\n[[Category:Academies in Medway]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name          = Greenacre Academy\n| image         = \n| image_size          = \n| logo = File:Fair use logo Greenacre Academy.png \n| caption       = \n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.3507|0.5256|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto         = \n| established   =  \n| closed        = \n| type          = Secondary Modern (non-selective)<ref name=\"Ofsted Report 2018\"/> [[Academy (English school)|Academy]] \n| trust         = [https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/Groups/Group/Details/3243 Skills for life trust]  UID: 3243\n| religious_affiliation      = \n| president     = \n| head_label    =  \n| head          =  Mrs S Bridger\n| r_head_label  = \n| r_head        = \n| chair_label   = \n| chair         = \n| founder       = \n| address        = 157 Walderslade Road\n| city          = [[Walderslade]]\n| county        = [[Kent]]\n| country       = [[England]]\n| postcode      = ME5 0LP\n| dfeno         = 887/4174\n| urn           = 138046\n| ofsted        = yes\n| capacity      =\n| enrolment    = 913 {{As of|2015|12|lc=on}}\n| gender        = Boys\n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 18\n| houses        = \n| colours       =   \n| publication   = \n| free_label_1  = \n| free_1        = \n| free_label_2  = \n| free_2        = \n| free_label_3  = \n| free_3        = \n| website       = {{url|www.sflt.org.uk/greenacre/}}\n| module ={{OSM Location map\n | float = centre\n | width = 250\n | coord = {{coord|51.3729|0.5251}} <!-- Centred -->\n | mark-coord = {{coord|51.3507|0.5256}} | label = Greenacre School| label-pos = bottom |label-offset-x = 0\n | zoom = 12}} <!-- marking the school-->\n}}\n\n'''Greenacre Academy''' (formerly Greenacre School and before that Walderslade Boys School), is a boys' [[secondary school]] with shared [[sixth form]] located in [[Walderslade]] in the [[English county]] of [[Kent]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.school-portal.co.uk/GroupHomepage.asp?GroupId=326530 |title=Greenacre Academy ** |publisher=School-portal.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2013-12-14}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Medway Council|Medway]], as a former part of Kent retains selection, so Walderslade Boys School opened as a [[Secondary Modern]], taking the boys who had been deemed unacademic. Students in Medway must still take an eleven plus exam, and the more able students are creamed off to one of several grammar schools. Kent and Medway euphemistically call these 'high schools' It had the status of a 11-18\n[[Community school (England and Wales)|community school]] <ref name=\"Ofsted Report 2011\">{{cite web |title=Ofsted Report 2011 |url=https://files.ofsted.gov.uk/v1/file/1967157 |website=ofsted.gov.uk |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> school converted to [[Academy (English school)|academy status]] on 1 April 2012 and was renamed '''Greenacre Academy'''.\n<ref name=\"GIAS 2020\">{{cite web |title=Greenacre Academy - GOV.UK |url=https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/Establishments/Establishment/Details/138046 |website=get-information-schools.service.gov.uk |accessdate=2 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nIt was previously a [[Community school (England and Wales)|community school]] administered by [[Medway Council]]; the school converted to [[Academy (English school)|academy status]] on 1 April 2012 and was renamed Greenacre Academy. The school continues to coordinate with Medway Council for admissions.<ref name=\"GIAS 2020\"/>\n\nIt is part of the [[Skills for life trust]], which contains: '''Greenacre Academy''', [[Walderslade Girls School]], Warren Wood Primary Academy, Chantry Community Academy, Hilltop Primary Academy, Kloisters Kindergarten and Pre-School, PGW Sixth Form and Greenacre Sports Partnership.<ref name=\"SKILLS FOR LIFE TRUST\">{{cite web |title=SKILLS FOR LIFE TRUST - GOV.UK |url=https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/Groups/Group/Details/3243#list |website=get-information-schools.service.gov.uk |accessdate=1 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nOfsted rated this as a \u01f4ood School in 2014 and 2018. The school is strong in establishing good behaviour as one of its 'Skills for Life'. Pupils enter the school with lower than average literacy skills which are targetted. <ref name=\"Ofsted Report 2018\">{{cite web |title=Ofsted Report 2018 |url=https://files.ofsted.gov.uk/v1/file/2780689 |website=ofsted.gov.uk |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe school offers a three-year [[Key Stage 3]] where the core subjects of the National Curriculum are taught.<ref name=\"Website-KS3-4-and-5\">{{cite web |title=Website-KS3-4-and-5 |url=http://www.sflt.org.uk/greenacre/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2016/09/Website-KS3-4-and-5.pdf |website=www.sflt.org.uk/greenacre |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt [[Key Stage 4]], the academy offers [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSEs]], [[Business and Technology Education Council|BTECs]], [[OCR Nationals]] and [[National Vocational Qualification|NVQs]] as programmes of study for pupils. The subjects are English (Literature and Language), Maths, Science and Skills for Life. Students may study the English Baccalaureate as they are offered options of: Modern Foreign Languages, Computing and Humanities (History and Geography). Further choices are availabe to selected student.<ref name=\"Website-KS3-4-and-5\"/> Ofsted considers the rate of progress for students at the lower end is good, but the higher ability pupils underperform.<ref name=\"Ofsted Report 2018\"/>\n\nThe school also operates a sixth form provision in partnership with [[Walderslade Girls' School]], with students having the option to study from a range of [[GCE Advanced Level|A Levels]] and further BTECs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pgwsixthform.co.uk/ |title=PGW Sixth Form |publisher=PGW Sixth Form |date= |accessdate=2013-12-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214184130/http://www.pgwsixthform.co.uk/ |archive-date=14 December 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sflt.org.uk/greenacre/ Greenacre Academy Trust official website]\n\n{{Schools in Kent}}\n\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Medway]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in Kent]]\n[[Category:Academies in Medway]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: a 11 \u2192 an 11, availabe \u2192 available", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greenacre_Academy"}
{"title_page": "Roseau Cathedral", "text_new": "{{Infobox religious building\n|building_name=Our Lady of Fair Haven of Roseau\n|image= Roseau Cathedral.jpg \n|image_size=250px\n|caption= Roseau Cathedral\n|location=  {{flag|Dominica }}\n| map_type              =Dominica\n| map_size              = 250\n| map_caption           =\n|coordinates           = {{coord|15.2975|-61.3853|display=inline,title}}\n|religious_affiliation=[[Roman Catholic]]\n|rite=\n|province=[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Castries|Archdiocese of Castries]]\n|district=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Roseau|Diocese of Dominica]]\n|consecration_year= 1916 (1925?)\n|status=\n|leadership= Bishop Gabriel Malzaire<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/rose0.htm |title=Diocese of Roseau, Dominica |website=Gcatholic.org |date= |accessdate=2016-02-18}}</ref>\n|website= {{url|http://www.dioceseofroseau.org/}}\n|architect=\n|architecture_type= [[Cathedral]], [[parish church]]\n|architecture_style= [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] revival style. \n|specifications=yes\n|facade_direction= East-northeast\n|groundbreaking= Initially in 1730, then in 1816, 1855, 1873 and finally in the 20th century\n|year_completed= 1916 (1925?)\n|construction_cost=\n|capacity=\n|length= \n|width= \n|width_nave= \n|height_max= \n|materials=Volcanic stones\n}}\n\nThe '''Cathedral of Our Lady of Fair Haven of Roseau''', originally known in French as '''{{lang|fr|\u00c9glise de Notre-Dame du Bon Port du Mouillage de Roseau}}''',<ref group=\"Notes\">Sometimes called the ''\"Catholic Cathedral of our Lady of Assumption\"''</ref> is a [[Roman Catholic]] [[cathedral]] in [[Roseau]], the capital city of [[Dominica]] in the [[Caribbean]]. The church is the [[Episcopal see|see]] of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Roseau|Diocese of Dominica]], [[suffragan diocese]] of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Castries|Archdiocese of Castries]], [[Saint Lucia]].\n\nThe cathedral is an example of [[Europe]]an [[creolisation]] influence in Dominica. Built in the [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic]] [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque revival]] style, the Cathedral's consecration, in its present form, is dated to 1916. Though it may appear small from the outside, the interior is spacious and well lit.<ref name=\"Crask2008\">{{cite book|author=Paul Crask|title=Dominica|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BQyakcstEWoC&pg=PA78|accessdate=20 June 2011|date=26 February 2008|publisher=Bradt Travel Guides|isbn=978-1-84162-217-0|pages=78\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nWhile [[Kalinago]] people originally called the region ''Sairi'', French woodcutters named the city Roseau, in the 18th century.<ref name=\"McCanse2011\">{{cite book|author=Anna McCanse|title=Dominica (Other Places Travel Guide)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Cpyw8DutnbMC&pg=PT104|accessdate=20 June 2011|date=3 May 2011|publisher=Other Places Publishing|isbn=978-0-9822619-7-2|pages=104, 112}}</ref> ''Roseau'' ({{lang|fr|reed}}) is the name of the river, the town, and the cathedral. The cathedral, originally called in French \"{{lang|fr|\u00c9glise de Notre-Dame du Bon Port du Mouillage de Roseau}}\",<ref group=\"Notes\">In English: ''Our Lady of the Good Haven of the Mooring of Roseau''</ref> is popularly known as \"Our Lady of Fair Haven\".<ref name=\"Crask2008\"/><ref name=\"Pizzichini2010\">{{cite book|last=Pizzichini|first=Lilian|title=Blue Hour|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l2Pn3jYF_M0C&pg=PA30|accessdate=22 June 2011|date=11 June 2010|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc|isbn=978-1-4088-0122-2|page=30}}</ref> It was also known at one time as \"Our Lady of Bon Port\".<ref name=\"Catholic directory, almanac and registry of Ireland, England and Scotland\">{{cite book|title=Catholic directory, almanac and registry of Ireland, England and Scotland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o6gpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA307|accessdate=20 June 2011|year=1865|publisher=J. Mullany.|pages=307\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Southern Roseau.png|thumb|left|230px|Map of southern Roseau. Roseau Cathedral is the landmark marked with a cross. Click twice to enlarge.]]\nThe location of the cathedral is in the southern part of the town of Roseau  on the banks of the Roseau River, which assures a good water supply. The availability of a large plane of land on the south river bank also dictated the cathedral's location.<ref name=\"Crask2008\"/><ref name=\"SarnaHannafin2004\">{{cite book|author1=Heidi Sarna|author2=Matt Hannafin|title=Frommer's Caribbean Ports of Call|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bFRwEM_IM2IC&pg=PA178|accessdate=20 June 2011|date=August 2004|publisher=Frommer's|isbn=978-0-7645-6899-2|pages=178\u2013}}</ref> The cathedral is located to the north of the [[Fort Young Hotel]] and northeast of the [[Dominica Museum]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Dominica church.jpg|thumb|Exterior view of the cathedral.]]\n[[File:Roseau Virgin Ln - Our Lady of Fair Haven Cathedral - panoramio.jpg|thumb|Panoramic view of the cathedral from the front.]]\nThe church at Roseau was initially a small wood hut with a thatched roof made of locally available reed. [[Kalina people|Carib people]] built the cathedral in the local building tradition.<ref name=\"McCanse2011\" />\n\n;18th century\nIn 1727, the plot of land was first surveyed for building. Three years later, in 1730, Father Guillaume Martel established a permanent church. He planned and built a {{convert|12|m}} by {{convert|5|m}} church made of solid wood (timber-framed<ref name=\"Gravette2000\"/>) and stone flooring, to meet the growing congregational needs of settlers who had come from France and occupied territory on the south coast of the island nation.\n\nIn April 1796, [[Agostino Brunias]] was buried in the Catholic cemetery, located at the site of the church.<ref name=\"MeeksLindahl2001\">{{cite book|last1=Meeks|first1=Brian|last2=Lindahl|first2=Folke|title=New Caribbean thought: a reader|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mUC4PA7ZedYC&pg=PA250|accessdate=22 June 2011|year=2001|publisher=University of the West Indies Press|isbn=978-976-640-103-0|page=250}}</ref>\n\n;19th century\nThis church survived until 1816 when it was destroyed by hurricane. The present church, which was built 24 years later, located at the same site, was also found to be inadequate to meet the growing needs of church goers. This was a result of abolition of slavery and permitting former slaves to attend church services. Black and white people sat together to worship in the pews without discrimination. The expansion program which began took almost 100 years to complete to its present form. The additions to the cathedral started with a steeple built in 1855, followed by a wooden ceiling for the cathedral in 1865 by the Kalinagos who cut and brought [[Bursera simaruba|simaruba]] trees from the northeast of Roseau; it took them three months to build the wooden ceiling. During this period, a large stone pulpit was also erected. This stone pulpit was carved by prisoners who were kept in [[Devil's Island]] (located off the coast of French Guiana).<ref name=\"Crask2008\"/><ref>{{cite book |author=Heidi Sarna & Matt Hannafin |year=2004 |title=Frommer's Caribbean Ports of Call |edition=5th |publisher=[[Frommer's]] |isbn=978-0-7645-6899-2 |chapter=Dominica |pages=174\u2013180 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=bFRwEM_IM2IC&pg=PA178}}</ref> In the year 1873, at the southeast end, the Chapel of St. Joseph came to be established along with a [[crypt]] where bishops and priests could be buried.<ref name=\"Crask2008\"/><ref name=\"McCanse2011\"/> In 1853, the town and the parish had a population of 6000 Catholics.  As the Catholic Ministry did not support the building activity, the Catholic community carried stones to the site to build the church.<ref name=\"Gravette2000\">{{cite book|author=Andrew Gerald Gravette|title=Architectural heritage of the Caribbean: an A-Z of historic buildings|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=US59JbQ6-OYC&pg=PA169|accessdate=21 June 2011|year=2000|publisher=Signal Books|isbn=978-1-902669-09-0|pages=169\u2013170}}</ref> A hurricane in 1863 caused substantial damage to the cathedral, which necessitated raising funds not only for its restoration, but also for many other churches on the island, which also had been destroyed by the hurricane. Funds were raised by imposing a levy <ref>McCanse (2011) p. 112</ref> on the French planters.\n\n;20th century\nFollowing this, refurbishing started with stained-glass windows being added to the church, and the addition of new stone pillars in 1902. The [[Steeple (architecture)|steeple]] was added on the western end, which was built with stones brought from the old church at [[Point Michael]] and then demolished. Building this part of the church brought symmetry to the cathedral\u2019s fa\u00e7ade. Mention is also made that the cathedral's [[spire]] was completed in 1916.<ref name=\"Gravette2000\"/> The cathedral was formally consecrated in 1925 by Bishop James Morris. After 1925, only minor additions in the form of electrical connections, a public address system and a clock have been made.\n\n==Architecture and fittings==\n[[File:Dominica (231).jpg|right|thumb|Spacious interior view of the cathedral.]]\nThe cathedral is on Virgin Lane west of the Methodist Church. It is a stone edifice with an expansive interior.<ref name=\"GorryMiller2005\">{{cite book|author1=Conner Gorry|author2=Debra Miller|title=Caribbean Islands|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JJObOeOb0wEC&pg=PA543|accessdate=20 June 2011|year=2005|publisher=Lonely Planet|isbn=978-1-74104-055-5|pages=543\u2013}}</ref> The Gothic Romanesque Revival style building is constructed of volcanic rock,<ref name=\"McCanse2011\"/> both inside and out, and is built to withstand earthquakes. The bell tower is stubby with a giant clock.<ref name=\"Mass\u00e91988\">{{cite book|author=Armand Mass\u00e9|title=Diaries of abb\u00e9 Mass\u00e9, 1878\u20131883|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zglsAAAAMAAJ|page=57|accessdate=20 June 2011|year=1988|isbn=978-976-8012-15-9}}</ref><ref name=\"John2011\">{{cite book|author=Giftus R John|title=Ma William and Her Circle of Friends|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=98lW60TcDKMC&pg=PA198|accessdate=20 June 2011|date=1 June 2011|publisher=iUniverse|isbn=978-1-4620-0752-3|pages=198\u2013}}</ref> The windows are Gothic with stained glass in the upper section and aligned wooden shutters in the lower sections, to provide good ventilation.  One of the stained glass windows is dedicated to [[Christopher Columbus]].  The building is well maintained.<ref name=\"GorryMiller2005\"/>\n\nThe interior of the cathedral is finely carved and has Victorian pews.<ref name=\"Gravette2000\"/> There are ornate Victorian murals behind the side altars, painted by the local artists.<ref name=\"McCanse2011\"/> The east and west walls have windows from the entrance to the altar. The organ in the cathedral was installed in January 1883.<ref name=\"Borom\u00e9Dominica1972\">{{cite book|author1=Joseph Alfred Borom\u00e9|author2=Dominica|title=Aspects of Dominican history|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fMVrAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=20 June 2011|year=1972|publisher=Government Print. Division}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{Reflist|group=\"Notes\"}}\n;Citations\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat-inline|Roseau Cathedral}}\n\n[[Category:Roman Catholic cathedrals in Dominica]]\n[[Category:19th-century Roman Catholic church buildings]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches completed in 1916]]\n[[Category:Gothic Revival church buildings]]\n[[Category:Romanesque Revival church buildings]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox religious building\n|building_name=Our Lady of Fair Haven of Roseau\n|image= Roseau Cathedral.jpg \n|image_size=250px\n|caption= Roseau Cathedral\n|location=  {{flag|Dominica }}\n| map_type              =Dominica\n| map_size              = 250\n| map_caption           =\n|coordinates           = {{coord|15.2975|-61.3853|display=inline,title}}\n|religious_affiliation=[[Roman Catholic]]\n|rite=\n|province=[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Castries|Archdiocese of Castries]]\n|district=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Roseau|Diocese of Dominica]]\n|consecration_year= 1916 (1925?)\n|status=\n|leadership= Bishop Gabriel Malzaire<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/rose0.htm |title=Diocese of Roseau, Dominica |website=Gcatholic.org |date= |accessdate=2016-02-18}}</ref>\n|website= {{url|http://www.dioceseofroseau.org/}}\n|architect=\n|architecture_type= [[Cathedral]], [[parish church]]\n|architecture_style= [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] revival style. \n|specifications=yes\n|facade_direction= East-northeast\n|groundbreaking= Initially in 1730, then in 1816, 1855, 1873 and finally in the 20th century\n|year_completed= 1916 (1925?)\n|construction_cost=\n|capacity=\n|length= \n|width= \n|width_nave= \n|height_max= \n|materials=Volcanic stones\n}}\n\nThe '''Cathedral of Our Lady of Fair Haven of Roseau''', originally known in French as '''{{lang|fr|\u00c9glise de Notre-Dame du Bon Port du Mouillage de Roseau}}''',<ref group=\"Notes\">Sometimes called the ''\"Catholic Cathedral of our Lady of Assumption\"''</ref> is a [[Roman Catholic]] [[cathedral]] in [[Roseau]], the capital city of [[Dominica]] in the [[Caribbean]]. The church is the [[Episcopal see|see]] of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Roseau|Diocese of Dominica]], [[suffragan diocese]] of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Castries|Archdiocese of Castries]], [[Saint Lucia]].\n\nThe cathedral is an example of [[Europe]]an [[creolisation]] influence in Dominica. Built in the [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic]] [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque revival]] style, the Cathedral's consecration, in its present form, is dated to 1916. Though it may appear small from the outside, the interior is spacious and well lit.<ref name=\"Crask2008\">{{cite book|author=Paul Crask|title=Dominica|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BQyakcstEWoC&pg=PA78|accessdate=20 June 2011|date=26 February 2008|publisher=Bradt Travel Guides|isbn=978-1-84162-217-0|pages=78\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nWhile [[Kalinago]] people originally called the region ''Sairi'', French woodcutters named the city Roseau, in the 18th century.<ref name=\"McCanse2011\">{{cite book|author=Anna McCanse|title=Dominica (Other Places Travel Guide)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Cpyw8DutnbMC&pg=PT104|accessdate=20 June 2011|date=3 May 2011|publisher=Other Places Publishing|isbn=978-0-9822619-7-2|pages=104, 112}}</ref> ''Roseau'' ({{lang|fr|reed}}) is the name of the river, the town, and the cathedral. The cathedral, originally called in French \"{{lang|fr|\u00c9glise de Notre-Dame du Bon Port du Mouillage de Roseau}}\",<ref group=\"Notes\">In English: ''Our Lady of the Good Haven of the Mooring of Roseau''</ref> is popularly known as \"Our Lady of Fair Haven\".<ref name=\"Crask2008\"/><ref name=\"Pizzichini2010\">{{cite book|last=Pizzichini|first=Lilian|title=Blue Hour|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l2Pn3jYF_M0C&pg=PA30|accessdate=22 June 2011|date=11 June 2010|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc|isbn=978-1-4088-0122-2|page=30}}</ref> It was also known at one time as \"Our Lady of Bon Port\".<ref name=\"Catholic directory, almanac and registry of Ireland, England and Scotland\">{{cite book|title=Catholic directory, almanac and registry of Ireland, England and Scotland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o6gpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA307|accessdate=20 June 2011|year=1865|publisher=J. Mullany.|pages=307\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Southern Roseau.png|thumb|left|230px|Map of southern Roseau. Roseau Cathedral is the landmark marked with a cross. Click twice to enlarge.]]\nThe location of the cathedral in the southern part of the town of Roseau  on the banks of the Roseau River, which assures a good water supply. The availability of a large plane of land on the south river bank also dictated the cathedral's location.<ref name=\"Crask2008\"/><ref name=\"SarnaHannafin2004\">{{cite book|author1=Heidi Sarna|author2=Matt Hannafin|title=Frommer's Caribbean Ports of Call|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bFRwEM_IM2IC&pg=PA178|accessdate=20 June 2011|date=August 2004|publisher=Frommer's|isbn=978-0-7645-6899-2|pages=178\u2013}}</ref> The cathedral is located to the north of the [[Fort Young Hotel]] and northeast of the [[Dominica Museum]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Dominica church.jpg|thumb|Exterior view of the cathedral.]]\n[[File:Roseau Virgin Ln - Our Lady of Fair Haven Cathedral - panoramio.jpg|thumb|Panoramic view of the cathedral from the front.]]\nThe church at Roseau was initially a small wood hut with a thatched roof made of locally available reed. [[Kalina people|Carib people]] built the cathedral in the local building tradition.<ref name=\"McCanse2011\" />\n\n;18th century\nIn 1727, the plot of land was first surveyed for building. Three years later, in 1730, Father Guillaume Martel established a permanent church. He planned and built a {{convert|12|m}} by {{convert|5|m}} church made of solid wood (timber-framed<ref name=\"Gravette2000\"/>) and stone flooring, to meet the growing congregational needs of settlers who had come from France and occupied territory on the south coast of the island nation.\n\nIn April 1796, [[Agostino Brunias]] was buried in the Catholic cemetery, located at the site of the church.<ref name=\"MeeksLindahl2001\">{{cite book|last1=Meeks|first1=Brian|last2=Lindahl|first2=Folke|title=New Caribbean thought: a reader|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mUC4PA7ZedYC&pg=PA250|accessdate=22 June 2011|year=2001|publisher=University of the West Indies Press|isbn=978-976-640-103-0|page=250}}</ref>\n\n;19th century\nThis church survived until 1816 when it was destroyed by hurricane. The present church, which was built 24 years later, located at the same site, was also found to be inadequate to meet the growing needs of church goers. This was a result of abolition of slavery and permitting former slaves to attend church services. Black and white people sat together to worship in the pews without discrimination. The expansion program which began took almost 100 years to complete to its present form. The additions to the cathedral started with a steeple built in 1855, followed by a wooden ceiling for the cathedral in 1865 by the Kalinagos who cut and brought [[Bursera simaruba|simaruba]] trees from the northeast of Roseau; it took them three months to build the wooden ceiling. During this period, a large stone pulpit was also erected. This stone pulpit was carved by prisoners who were kept in [[Devil's Island]] (located off the coast of French Guiana).<ref name=\"Crask2008\"/><ref>{{cite book |author=Heidi Sarna & Matt Hannafin |year=2004 |title=Frommer's Caribbean Ports of Call |edition=5th |publisher=[[Frommer's]] |isbn=978-0-7645-6899-2 |chapter=Dominica |pages=174\u2013180 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=bFRwEM_IM2IC&pg=PA178}}</ref> In the year 1873, at the southeast end, the Chapel of St. Joseph came to be established along with a [[crypt]] where bishops and priests could be buried.<ref name=\"Crask2008\"/><ref name=\"McCanse2011\"/> In 1853, the town and the parish had a population of 6000 Catholics.  As the Catholic Ministry did not support the building activity, the Catholic community carried stones to the site to build the church.<ref name=\"Gravette2000\">{{cite book|author=Andrew Gerald Gravette|title=Architectural heritage of the Caribbean: an A-Z of historic buildings|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=US59JbQ6-OYC&pg=PA169|accessdate=21 June 2011|year=2000|publisher=Signal Books|isbn=978-1-902669-09-0|pages=169\u2013170}}</ref> A hurricane in 1863 caused substantial damage to the cathedral, which necessitated raising funds not only for its restoration, but also for many other churches on the island, which also had been destroyed by the hurricane. Funds were raised by imposing a levy <ref>McCanse (2011) p. 112</ref> on the French planters.\n\n;20th century\nFollowing this, refurbishing started with stained-glass windows being added to the church, and the addition of new stone pillars in 1902. The [[Steeple (architecture)|steeple]] was added on the western end, which was built with stones brought from the old church at [[Point Michael]] and then demolished. Building this part of the church brought symmetry to the cathedral\u2019s fa\u00e7ade. Mention is also made that the cathedral's [[spire]] was completed in 1916.<ref name=\"Gravette2000\"/> The cathedral was formally consecrated in 1925 by Bishop James Morris. After 1925, only minor additions in the form of electrical connections, a public address system and a clock have been made.\n\n==Architecture and fittings==\n[[File:Dominica (231).jpg|right|thumb|Spacious interior view of the cathedral.]]\nThe cathedral is on Virgin Lane west of the Methodist Church. It is a stone edifice with an expansive interior.<ref name=\"GorryMiller2005\">{{cite book|author1=Conner Gorry|author2=Debra Miller|title=Caribbean Islands|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JJObOeOb0wEC&pg=PA543|accessdate=20 June 2011|year=2005|publisher=Lonely Planet|isbn=978-1-74104-055-5|pages=543\u2013}}</ref> The Gothic Romanesque Revival style building is constructed of volcanic rock,<ref name=\"McCanse2011\"/> both inside and out, and is built to withstand earthquakes. The bell tower is stubby with a giant clock.<ref name=\"Mass\u00e91988\">{{cite book|author=Armand Mass\u00e9|title=Diaries of abb\u00e9 Mass\u00e9, 1878\u20131883|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zglsAAAAMAAJ|page=57|accessdate=20 June 2011|year=1988|isbn=978-976-8012-15-9}}</ref><ref name=\"John2011\">{{cite book|author=Giftus R John|title=Ma William and Her Circle of Friends|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=98lW60TcDKMC&pg=PA198|accessdate=20 June 2011|date=1 June 2011|publisher=iUniverse|isbn=978-1-4620-0752-3|pages=198\u2013}}</ref> The windows are Gothic with stained glass in the upper section and aligned wooden shutters in the lower sections, to provide good ventilation.  One of the stained glass windows is dedicated to [[Christopher Columbus]].  The building is well maintained.<ref name=\"GorryMiller2005\"/>\n\nThe interior of the cathedral is finely carved and has Victorian pews.<ref name=\"Gravette2000\"/> There are ornate Victorian murals behind the side altars, painted by the local artists.<ref name=\"McCanse2011\"/> The east and west walls have windows from the entrance to the altar. The organ in the cathedral was installed in January 1883.<ref name=\"Borom\u00e9Dominica1972\">{{cite book|author1=Joseph Alfred Borom\u00e9|author2=Dominica|title=Aspects of Dominican history|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fMVrAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=20 June 2011|year=1972|publisher=Government Print. Division}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{Reflist|group=\"Notes\"}}\n;Citations\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat-inline|Roseau Cathedral}}\n\n[[Category:Roman Catholic cathedrals in Dominica]]\n[[Category:19th-century Roman Catholic church buildings]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches completed in 1916]]\n[[Category:Gothic Revival church buildings]]\n[[Category:Romanesque Revival church buildings]]\n", "name_user": "Jzsj", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roseau_Cathedral"}
