ament|1992]]\n|conference_tournament = \n|conference_season = 1987\n|uniform_image = WCHA-Uniform-UAA.png\n}}\n\nThe '''Alaska Anchorage Seawolves men's ice hockey''' team is a [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] [[college ice hockey]] program that represents the [[University of Alaska Anchorage]]. The Seawolves are a member of the [[Western Collegiate Hockey Association]] (WCHA). They play at the [[Sullivan Arena]] in [[Anchorage, Alaska]].<ref>{{cite web |publisher=U.S. College Hockey Online|url=http://www.uscho.com/team/alaska-anchorage/mens-hockey/|title=Alaska-Anchorage Seawolves Men's Hockey|accessdate=May 1, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[University of Alaska Anchorage|UAA]] began its ice hockey program in 1979, playing 8 of its 31 games against [[NCAA Division II|Division II]] [[Alaska Nanooks men's ice hockey |Alaska\u2013Fairbanks]] (winning all) before beginning a full D-II schedule the following season. The Seawolves rose quickly in the Division II ranks, narrowly missing out on the NCAA tournament in [[1984 NCAA Division II Men's Ice Hockey Tournament|1984]] but promoted the team to [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] that summer when the entire D-II division collapsed.<ref name=ncaa>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncaa.sports.hopeark.com/icehockey-mens |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413142938/http://www.ncaa.sports.hopeark.com/icehockey-mens |url-status=dead |archive-date=2014-04-13 |title=NCAA page for men's ice hockey |accessdate=2008-05-15 |work=NCAA.com }} </ref>\n\nAnchorage played as an independent for a year before being a founding member of the first west coast conference, the [[Great West Hockey Conference]]. The league was very short-lived, lasting only three seasons before the two non-Alaska schools dropped hockey entirely, but it did provide UAA with its first league title in [[1986\u201387 NCAA Division I men's ice hockey season|1987]].<ref name=\"CHHA\">{{cite web |title=History of the Great West Hockey Conference |url=http://www.augenblick.org/chha/gwc_his.html |work=College Hockey Historical Archives |accessdate=February 2, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6E8cgiw4J?url=http://www.augenblick.org/chha/gwc_his.html |archivedate=February 2, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Seawolves were once again without a conference in 1988\u201389, but a year later they posted their first 20-win season at the D-I level and were selected to the [[1990 NCAA Division I Men's Ice Hockey Tournament|NCAA Tournament]].\n\nThe Seawolves dropped both games to [[Lake Superior State Lakers men's ice hockey|Lake Superior State]] but returned the following year after another 20-win campaign and this time they were able to win their first NCAA round, defeating the [[Boston College Eagles men's ice hockey|Boston College Eagles]]. [[1991\u201392 NCAA Division I men's ice hockey season|1991\u201392]] provided UAA with its best record, with the team going 27\u20138\u20131 and garnering a third consecutive NCAA berth (the last such for UAA as of 2019). After one more winning season the Seawolves joined the [[Western Collegiate Hockey Association]].\n\nThe stability of their new conference came as a double-edged sword, however, as the Seawolves would spend the next 20 years finishing with losing records. To make matters worse the team would lost both games in the opening round of the [[List of WCHA Men's Ice Hockey Tournament champions|WCHA tournament]] most of the time and only twice could manage a First Round series win.\n\nThe college hockey world changed in 2013 when the [[Central Collegiate Hockey Association]] collapsed due to the formation of the [[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]] and the [[National Collegiate Hockey Conference]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The CCHA is going away, but its history will have a final resting place|url=http://www.uscho.com/2013/03/06/the-ccha-is-going-away-but-its-history-will-have-a-final-resting-place/|publisher=USCHO.com|date=2013-03-06|accessdate=2013-07-23}}</ref> This caused the WCHA to replace many of its departing members with weaker teams but even in the new WCHA UAA was still a bottom-half team. After making the conference semifinals the first season the Seawolves missed the playoffs each of the next five years.\n\n==Season-by-season results<ref>{{cite news|title=Alaska Anchorage Hockey Media Guide|url=http://www.goseawolves.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=13400&ATCLID=1602924|publisher=Go Seawolves.com|accessdate=2018-05-18}}</ref>==\n\n{{Main article|List of Alaska Anchorage Seawolves men's ice hockey seasons}}\n\n==Head Coaches==\n{| cellpadding=\"1\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"80%\"\n! style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Alaska Anchorage Seawolves|color=white}};\" | Tenure\n! style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Alaska Anchorage Seawolves|color=white}};\" | Coach\n! style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Alaska Anchorage Seawolves|color=white}};\" | Years\n! style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Alaska Anchorage Seawolves|color=white}};\" | Record\n! style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Alaska Anchorage Seawolves|color=white}};\" | Pct.\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 1979&ndash;1996 || [[Brush Christiansen]] || 17 || 287\u2013229\u201330 || {{winpct|287|229|30}}\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 1996&ndash;2001 || [[Dean Talafous]] || 5 || 50\u2013108\u201322 || {{winpct|50|108|22}}\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 2001&ndash;2005 || [[John Hill (ice hockey)|John Hill]] || 4 || 39\u201389\u201321 || {{winpct|39|89|21}}\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 2005&ndash;2013 || [[Dave Shyiak]] || 8 || 80\u2013177\u201333 || {{winpct|80|177|33}}\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 2013&ndash;2018|| [[Matt Thomas (ice hockey)|Matt Thomas]] || 5 || 48\u2013105\u201321 || {{winpct|48|105|21}}\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 2018&ndash;Present|| [[Matt Curley]] || 1 || 3\u201328\u20133|| {{winpct|3|28|3}}\n|- align=\"center\"\n|- align=\"center\"\n|- align=center\n! style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Alaska Anchorage Seawolves|color=white}};\" | Totals\n! style=\"{{CollegePrimarySty